# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: african-american-music
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] This article includes an overview of the events and trends in **popular music in the 1960s**.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] In North America and Europe the decade was particularly revolutionary in terms of popular music, continuing the shift away from traditional pop that began in the 1950s.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The 1960s saw the evolution of rock and the beginnings of the album era.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] At the beginning of the 1960s, pop and rock and roll trends of the 1950s continued; nevertheless, the rock and roll of the decade before started to merge into a more international, electric variant.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] In the mid-1960s, rock and roll in its purest form was gradually overtaken by pop rock, beat, psychedelic rock, blues rock, and folk rock, which had grown in popularity.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The country- and folk-influenced style associated with the latter half of 1960s rock music spawned a generation of popular singer-songwriters who wrote and performed their own work.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Towards the decade's end, genres such as Baroque pop, sunshine pop, bubble gum pop, and progressive rock started to grow popular, with the latter two finding greater success in the following decade.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Furthermore, the 1960s saw funk and soul music rising in popularity; rhythm and blues in general remained popular.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The fusion of R&B, gospel, and original rock and roll was a success until the mid-part of the decade.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Aside from the popularity of rock and R&B music in the 1960s, Latin American as well as Jamaican and Cuban music achieved a degree of popularity throughout the decade, with genres such as bossa nova, the cha-cha-cha, ska, and calypso being popular.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] From a classical point of view, the 1960s were also an important decade as they saw the development of electronic, experimental, jazz and contemporary classical music, notably minimalism and free improvisation.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] In Asia, various trends marked the popular music of the 1960s.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] In Japan, the decade saw the rise in popularity of several Western popular music groups such as The Beatles and the Rolling Stones.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The success of rock music and bands in Japan started a new genre, known as Group Sounds, which was popular in the latter half of the decade.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] In South America, genres such as bossa nova, Nueva canción and Nueva ola started to rise.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Rock music began leaving its mark, and achieved success in the 1960s.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Additionally, salsa grew popular towards the end of the decade.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] In the 1960s cumbia entered Chile and left a long-lasting impact on tropical music in that country.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] In the late 1950s, a flourishing culture of groups began to emerge, often out of the declining skiffle scene, in major urban centres in the UK like Liverpool, Manchester, Birmingham and London.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] This was particularly true in Liverpool, where it has been estimated that there were around 350 different bands active, often playing ballrooms, concert halls and clubs.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Beat bands were heavily influenced by American bands of the era, such as Buddy Holly and the Crickets (from which group the Beatles derived their name), as well as earlier British groups such as the Shadows.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] After the national success of the Beatles in Britain from 1962, a number of Liverpool performers were able to follow them into the charts, including Cilla Black, Gerry and the Pacemakers and the Searchers.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Among the most successful beat acts from Birmingham were the Spencer Davis Group and the Moody Blues.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] From London, the term *Tottenham Sound* was largely based around the Dave Clark Five, but other London bands that benefited from the beat boom of this era included the Rolling Stones, the Yardbirds and the Kinks.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The first non-Liverpool, non-Brian Epstein-managed band to break through in the UK were Freddie and the Dreamers, who were based in Manchester, as were Herman's Hermits.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The beat movement provided most of the groups responsible for the British Invasion of the American pop charts in the period after 1964, and furnished the model for many important developments in pop and rock music.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] By the end of 1962, the British rock scene had started with beat groups like the Beatles drawing on a wide range of American influences including soul music, rhythm and blues and surf music.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Initially, they reinterpreted standard American tunes, playing for dancers doing the twist, for example.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] These groups eventually infused their original rock compositions with increasingly complex musical ideas and a distinctive sound.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] In mid-1962 the Rolling Stones started as one of a number of groups increasingly showing blues influence, along with bands like the Animals and the Yardbirds.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] During 1963, the Beatles and other beat groups, such as the Searchers and the Hollies, achieved great popularity and commercial success in Britain itself.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] British rock broke through to mainstream popularity in the United States in January 1964 with the success of the Beatles.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] "I Want to Hold Your Hand" was the band's first No.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] 1 hit on the *Billboard* Hot 100 chart, starting the British Invasion of the American music charts.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The song entered the chart on January 18, 1964, at No.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] 1 single for 7 weeks and went on to last a total of 15 weeks in the chart.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Their first appearance on *The Ed Sullivan Show* February 9 is considered a milestone in American pop culture.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The broadcast drew an estimated 73 million viewers, at the time a record for an American television program.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The Beatles went on to become the biggest selling rock band of all time and they were followed by numerous British bands.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] During the next two years, Chad & Jeremy, Peter and Gordon, the Animals, Manfred Mann, Petula Clark, Freddie and the Dreamers, Wayne Fontana and the Mindbenders, Herman's Hermits, the Rolling Stones, the Troggs, and Donovan would have one or more No.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Other acts that were part of the invasion included the Kinks and the Dave Clark Five.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] British Invasion acts also dominated the music charts at home in the United Kingdom.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The British Invasion helped internationalize the production of rock and roll, opening the door for subsequent British (and Irish) performers to achieve international success.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] In America it arguably spelled the end of instrumental surf music, vocal girl groups and (for a time) the teen idols, that had dominated the American charts in the late 1950s and 1960s.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] It dented the careers of established R&B acts like Fats Domino and Chubby Checker and even temporarily derailed the chart success of surviving rock and roll acts, including Elvis Presley.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The British Invasion also played a major part in the rise of a distinct genre of rock music, and cemented the primacy of the rock group, based on guitars and drums and producing their own material as singer-songwriters.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] In parallel with Beat music, in the late 1950s and early 1960s a British blues scene was developing recreating the sounds of American R&B and later particularly the sounds of bluesmen Robert Johnson, Howlin' Wolf and Muddy Waters.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] It reached its height of mainstream popularity in the 1960s, when it developed a distinctive and influential style dominated by electric guitar and made international stars of several proponents of the genre including the Rolling Stones, Eric Clapton, the Yardbirds, Fleetwood Mac and Led Zeppelin.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] A number of these moved through blues rock to different forms of rock music and as a result British blues helped to form many of the subgenres of rock, including psychedelic rock and heavy metal music.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Since then direct interest in the blues in Britain has declined, but many of the key performers have returned to it in recent years, new acts have emerged and there have been a renewed interest in the genre.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] British psychedelia emerged during the mid-1960s, was influenced by psychedelic culture and attempted to replicate and enhance the mind-altering experiences of hallucinogenic drugs.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The movement drew on non-Western sources such as Indian music's ragas and sitars as well as studio effects and long instrumental passages and surreal lyrics.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Established British artists such as Eric Burdon, the Who, Cream, Pink Floyd and the Beatles produced a number of highly psychedelic tunes during the decade.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Many British psychedelia bands of the 1960s never published their music and only appeared in live concerts during that time.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Roy Orbison was one of rock's famous artists who wrote ballads of lost love.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] In the early part of the decade, Elvis Presley continued to score hits.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] For most of the 60s, Presley mostly released films.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Presley decided to get away from films by 1969; his last #1 song on the charts was Suspicious Minds which was released in 1969.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] By the 1960s, the scene that had developed out of the American folk music revival had grown to a major movement, utilizing traditional music and new compositions in a traditional style, usually on acoustic instruments.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] In America the genre was pioneered by figures such as Woody Guthrie and Pete Seeger and often identified with progressive or labor politics.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] In the early sixties figures such as Bob Dylan, Chubby Checker, and Joan Baez had come to the fore in this movement as singer-songwriters.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Early attempts to combine elements of folk and rock included the Animals "House of the Rising Sun" (1964), which was the first commercially successful folk song to be recorded with rock and roll instrumentation.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The folk rock movement is usually thought to have taken off with the Byrds' recording of Dylan's "Mr.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Tambourine Man" which topped the charts in 1965.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] With members who had been part of the cafe-based folk scene in Los Angeles, the Byrds adopted rock instrumentation, including drums and 12-string Rickenbacker guitars, which became a major element in the sound of the genre.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] By the mid-'60s Bob Dylan took the lead in merging folk and rock, and in July '65, released Like a Rolling Stone, with a revolutionary rock sound, steeped in tawdry urban imagery, followed by an electric performance later that month at the Newport Folk Festival.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Dylan plugged an entire generation into the milieu of the singer-songwriter, often writing from an urban point of view, with poetry punctuated by rock rhythms and electric power.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] By the mid to late '60s, bands and singer-songwriters began to proliferate the underground New York art/music scene.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The release of *The Velvet Underground & Nico* in 1967, featuring singer-songwriter Lou Reed and German singer and collaborator Nico was described as "most prophetic rock album ever made" by *Rolling Stone* in 2003.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Other New York City based singer-songwriters began to emerge, using the urban landscape as their canvass for lyrics in the confessional style of poets like Anne Sexton and Sylvia Plath.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Dylan's adoptation of electric instruments, much to the outrage of many folk purists, with his "Like a Rolling Stone" succeeded in creating a new genre.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Folk rock reached its peak of commercial popularity in the period 1967–68, before many acts moved off in a variety of directions, including Dylan and the Byrds, who began to develop country rock.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] However, the hybridization of folk and rock has been seen as having a major influence on the development of rock music, bringing in elements of psychedelia, and in particular, helping to develop the ideas of the singer-songwriter, the protest song and concepts of "authenticity".
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Psychedelic music's LSD-inspired vibe began in the folk scene, with the New York-based Holy Modal Rounders using the term in their 1964 recording of "Hesitation Blues".
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The first group to advertise themselves as psychedelic rock were the 13th Floor Elevators from Texas, at the end of 1965; producing an album that made their direction clear, with *The Psychedelic Sounds of the 13th Floor Elevators* the following year.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Psychedelic rock particularly took off in California's emerging music scene as groups followed the Byrds from folk to folk rock from 1965.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The Los Angeles-based group the Doors formed in 1965 after a chance meeting on Venice Beach.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Although its charismatic lead singer Jim Morrison died in 1971, the band's popularity has endured to this day.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The psychedelic life style had already developed in San Francisco since about 1964, and particularly prominent products of the scene were the Grateful Dead, Country Joe and the Fish, the Great Society and Jefferson Airplane.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The Byrds rapidly progressed from purely folk rock in 1966 with their single "Eight Miles High", widely taken to be a reference to drug use.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Psychedelic rock reached its apogee in the last years of the decade.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] In America the Summer of Love was prefaced by the Human Be-In event and reached its peak at the Monterey Pop Festival, the latter helping to make major American stars of Jimi Hendrix and the Who, whose single "I Can See for Miles" delved into psychedelic territory.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Key recordings included Jefferson Airplane's *Surrealistic Pillow* and the Doors' *Strange Days*.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] These trends climaxed in the 1969 Woodstock Festival, which saw performances by most of the major psychedelic acts, but by the end of the decade psychedelic rock was in retreat.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The Jimi Hendrix Experience broke up before the end of the decade and many surviving acts moved away from psychedelia into more back-to-basics "roots rock", the wider experimentation of progressive rock, or riff laden heavy rock.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] In the early 1960s, one of the most popular forms of rock and roll was Surf Rock, which was characterized by being nearly entirely instrumental and by heavy use of reverb on the guitars.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The spring reverb featured in Fender amplifiers of the day, cranked to its maximum volume, produced a guitar tone shimmering with sustain and evoking surf and ocean imagery.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Duane Eddy's "Movin' and Groovin" is thought by many to be the main contender for laying the groundwork as the first surf rock record, while others claim the genre was invented by Dick Dale on "Let's Go Trippin'", which became a hit throughout California.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Most early surf bands were formed during this decade in the Southern California area.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Garage rock was a raw form of rock music, particularly prevalent in North America in the mid-1960s and is called such because of the perception that many of the bands rehearsed in a suburban family garage.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Garage rock songs often revolved around the traumas of high school life, with songs about "lying girls" being particularly common.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The lyrics and delivery were notably more aggressive than was common at the time, often with growled or shouted vocals that dissolved into incoherent screaming such as the influential Washington based band, The Sonics.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] They ranged from crude one-chord music (like the Seeds) to near-studio musician quality (including the Knickerbockers, the Remains, and the Fifth Estate).
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] There were also regional variations in many parts of the country with flourishing scenes particularly in California and Texas.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The Pacific Northwest states of Washington and Oregon had perhaps the most defined regional sound.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The style had been evolving from regional scenes as early as 1958.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] "Louie Louie" by the Kingsmen (1963) is a mainstream example of the genre in its formative stages.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] By 1963, garage band singles were creeping into the national charts in greater numbers, including Paul Revere and the Raiders (Boise), the Trashmen (Minneapolis) and the Rivieras (South Bend, Indiana).
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] In this early period many bands were heavily influenced by surf rock and there was a cross-pollination between garage rock and frat rock, sometimes viewed as merely a subgenre of garage rock.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The British Invasion of 1964–66 greatly influenced garage bands, providing them with a national audience, leading many (often surf or hot rod groups) to adopt a British Invasion lilt, and encouraging many more groups to form.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Thousands of garage bands were extant in the US and Canada during the era and hundreds produced regional hits.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Despite scores of bands being signed to major or large regional labels, most were commercial failures.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] It is generally agreed that garage rock peaked both commercially and artistically around 1966.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] By 1968 the style largely disappeared from the national charts and at the local level as amateur musicians faced college, work or the draft.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] New styles had evolved to replace garage rock (including blues-rock, progressive rock and country rock).
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] In Detroit garage rock stayed alive until the early '70s, with bands like the MC5 and the Stooges, who employed a much more aggressive style.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] These bands began to be labelled punk rock and are now often seen as proto-punk or proto-hard rock.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The American blues-rock had been pioneered in the early 1960s by guitarist Lonnie Mack, but the genre began to take off in the mid-'60s as acts followed developed a sound similar to British blues musicians.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Key acts included Paul Butterfield (whose band acted like Mayall's Bluesbreakers in Britain as a starting point for many successful musicians), Canned Heat, the early Jefferson Airplane, Janis Joplin, Johnny Winter, the J.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Geils Band and Jimi Hendrix with his power trios, the Jimi Hendrix Experience and Band of Gypsys, whose guitar virtuosity and showmanship would be among the most emulated of the decade.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Blues-rock bands like Allman Brothers Band, Lynyrd Skynyrd and eventually ZZ Top from the southern states, incorporated country elements into their style to produce distinctive Southern rock.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Roots rock is the term now used to describe a move away from the excesses of the psychedelic scene, to a more basic form of rock and roll that incorporated its original influences, particularly country and folk music, leading to the creation of country rock and Southern rock.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] In 1966, Bob Dylan spearheaded the movement when he went to Nashville to record the album *Blonde on Blonde*.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] This, and subsequent more clearly country-influenced albums, have been seen as creating the genre of country folk, a route pursued by a number of, largely acoustic, folk musicians.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Other acts that followed the back-to-basics trend were the group the Band and the Californian-based Creedence Clearwater Revival, both of which mixed basic rock and roll with folk, country and blues, to be among the most successful and influential bands of the late 1960s.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The same movement saw the beginning of the recording careers of Californian solo artists like Ry Cooder, Bonnie Raitt and Lowell George, and influenced the work of established performers such as the Rolling Stones' *Beggar's Banquet* (1968) and the Beatles' *Let It Be* (1970).
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] In 1968, Gram Parsons recorded *Safe at Home* with the International Submarine Band, arguably the first true country rock album.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Later that year he joined the Byrds for *Sweetheart of the Rodeo* (1968), generally considered one of the most influential recordings in the genre.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The Byrds continued in the same vein, but Parsons left to be joined by another ex-Byrds member Chris Hillman in forming the Flying Burrito Brothers who helped establish the respectability and parameters of the genre, before Parsons departed to pursue a solo career.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Country rock was particularly popular in the Californian music scene, where it was adopted by bands including Hearts & Flowers, Poco and Riders of the Purple Sage, the Beau Brummels and the Nitty Gritty Dirt Band.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] A number of performers also enjoyed a renaissance by adopting country sounds, including: the Everly Brothers; one-time teen idol Ricky Nelson who became the frontman for the Stone Canyon Band; former Monkee Mike Nesmith who formed the First National Band; and Neil Young.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The Dillards were, unusually, a country act, who moved towards rock music.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The founders of Southern rock are usually thought to be the Allman Brothers Band, who developed a distinctive sound, largely derived from blues rock, but incorporating elements of boogie, soul and country in the early 1970s.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The most successful act to follow them were Lynyrd Skynyrd, who helped establish the "good ol' boy" image of the subgenre and the general shape of 1970s guitar rock.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Their successors included the fusion/progressive instrumentalists Dixie Dregs, the more country-influenced Outlaws, jazz-leaning Wet Willie and (incorporating elements of R&B and gospel) the Ozark Mountain Daredevils.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] After the loss of original members of the Allmans and Lynyrd Skynyrd, the genre began to fade in popularity in the late 1970s, but was sustained the 1980s with acts like .38 Special, Molly Hatchet and the Marshall Tucker Band.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Progressive rock, sometimes used interchangeably with art rock, was an attempt to move beyond established musical formulas by experimenting with different instruments, song types and forms.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The Moody Blues used a full orchestra on their album *Days of Future Passed* (1967) and subsequently created orchestral sounds with synthesisers.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Classical orchestration, keyboards and synthesisers were a frequent edition to the established rock format of guitars, bass and drums in subsequent progressive rock.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Instrumentals were common, while songs with lyrics were sometimes conceptual, abstract or based in fantasy and science fiction.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Chubby Checker during the early 1960s popularizes the enduring dance craze the Twist with his hit cover of Hank Ballard & the Midnighters' R&B hit "The Twist".
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The Brill Building at 1619 Broadway in New York City became the centre of the American music industry that dominated the pop charts in the early 1960s, nurturing many prolific songwriting partnerships.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Gerry Goffin and Carole King become a very influential duo in pop music, writing numerous number-one hits including the first song to ever reach number-one by a girl group, The Shirelles "Will You Love Me Tomorrow" and the 1962 number-one hit, "The Loco-Motion" which was performed by Little Eva.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Other hits included "Take Good Care of My Baby" (Bobby Vee), "Up on the Roof" (The Drifters), "I'm Into Something Good" (Herman's Hermits), and "One Fine Day" (The Chiffons).
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] "Sugar, Sugar" becomes a big hit for The Archies, defining the bubblegum pop genre.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The Monkees were a made for TV band, inspired by the antics of the Beatles in A Hard Day's Night.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Under contractual reasons, the group were not allowed to play their own instruments, which led to many feuds between the bandmates and music supervisor, Don Kirshner.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The Monkees and The Archies were not unique; in fact, bands not playing their instruments on record was not unusual.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Producers like Mickie Most regularly used experienced session musicians whose discipline helped produce a number of tighter-sounding commercial recordings within one time-limited studio session (typically 3 hours).
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Studios and producers regularly experimented with session singers and musicians to create a hit.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] A single by The Rare Breed, "Beg Borrow And Steal", was picked up by a production company.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Triumph and great tragedy marked the 1960s in country music.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The genre continued to gain national exposure through network television, with weekly series and awards programs gaining popularity.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Sales of records continued to rise as new artists and trends came to the forefront.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] However, several top stars died under tragic circumstances, including several who were killed in plane crashes.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The predominant musical style during the decade was the Nashville Sound, a style that emphasized string sections, background vocals, crooning lead vocals and production styles seen in country music.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The style had first become popular in the late 1950s, in response to the growing encroachment of rock and roll on the country genre, but saw its greatest success in the 1960s.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Charles recorded covers of traditional country, folk and classical music standards in pop, R&B and jazz styles.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The album was hailed as a critical and commercial success, and would be vastly influential in later country music styles.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] By the end of the decade, the Nashville Sound became more polished and streamlined, and became known as "countrypolitan." Tammy Wynette, Glen Campbell, Dottie West and Charley Pride were among the top artists adopting this style.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] While George Jones — by the early 1960s one of country music's most consistent hitmakers — also recorded countrypolitan-styled music, his background remained pure honky tonk, singing of heartbreak and loneliness in many of his songs.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Also, Marty Robbins proved to be one of the genre's most diverse singers, singing everything from straight-ahead country to western to pop to blues ... and even Hawaiian.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] His music showed great compassion for minorities and others who were shunned by society, including prison inmates.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Two of Cash's most successful albums were recorded live in prison: *At Folsom Prison* and *At San Quentin*.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] During the latter half of the 1960s, Pride — a native of Sledge, Mississippi — became the first African-American superstar in country music, a genre virtually dominated by white artists.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] 1 hits on the *Billboard* Hot Country Singles chart.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Buck Owens, Merle Haggard and Wynn Stewart were some of the top artists adopting this sound, and by the late 1960s they were among country music's top selling artists.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The 1960s also marked the rise of a young Abbott, Texas, songwriter named Willie Nelson.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Starting as a disc jockey in the late 1950s, he began honing his craft and wrote his first hit, "Family Bible," which he sold the rights to guitar instructor Paul Buskirk before it eventually became a hit for Claude Gray in 1960.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] He recorded an album, *...And Then I Wrote*, and eventually signed with RCA Records, but during most of the 1960s, most of his single releases were mid-chart hits at best; his recording career would not come to full fruition until the mid-1970s, after he became associated with the outlaw movement.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Among female acts, the most successful of the lot were Loretta Lynn, Tammy Wynette and Dolly Parton.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Parton, a native of the Smoky Mountains town of Locust Ridge, Tennessee, gained national exposure on the nationally syndicated program *The Porter Wagoner Show*, on which she began appearing in 1967.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Two years earlier, she had signed a recording contract with Monument Records and was pushed as a bubblegum pop singer, but had only minor success before one of her compositions – "Put It Off Until Tomorrow" – became a big hit for Bill Phillips (a track which Parton provided backing vocals) in 1966.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Eventually, her mountain-influenced, biographical brand of country and her down-home personality won many fans, and her star power would only begin to rise.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Her first major hits were mainly duets with Wagoner, although she had several solo hits—including her breakthrough, "Dumb Blonde"—as well.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] By the late 1960s, she was married to fellow country music singer George Jones.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Among other female newcomers, Connie Smith was among the most successful, as her breakthrough hit, "Once a Day" spent eight weeks at No.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] 1 on the *Billboard* Hot Country Singles chart in late 1964 and early 1965, the longest-running chart-topper for nearly 50 years.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] During a career that has spanned 50-plus years, Smith's songs often explored themes of loneliness and vulnerability.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] In addition to the syndicated *The Porter Wagoner Show*, several other television programs were produced to allow country music to reach a wider audience, such as *The Jimmy Dean Show* in mid-decade.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The Academy of Country Music and Country Music Association awards programs were telecast for the first time in the late 1960s.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Johnny Horton, who sang in the saga-song style, was killed in a car accident in 1960.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] A March 5, 1963, plane crash claimed the lives of Patsy Cline, Cowboy Copas and Hawkshaw Hawkins.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Days later, Jack Anglin was killed in a car accident, while Texas Ruby died in a trailer fire in Texas.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] In July 1964, Jim Reeves lost his life while piloting a plane near Brentwood, Tennessee.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Ira Louvin (one half of the Louvin Brothers) was killed in a car accident in 1965.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Other pioneering stars who died during the 1960s included A.P.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Carter, Gid Tanner, Moon Mullican, Ernest "Pop" Stoneman, Red Foley, Leon Payne and Spade Cooley.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The 1960s began a trend toward a proliferation of No.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] 1 hits on the *Billboard* Hot Country Singles chart, thanks to ever-changing data collecting methods.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] When the 1960s decade opened, there were but four No.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] 1 songs topping the chart (five, if one counts Marty Robbins' "El Paso"), but by the mid-1960s, there were always at least a dozen songs topping the chart annually.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] In 1967, there were more than 20 songs reaching the top spot for the first time ever in a single calendar year ... and that number would only continue to rise during the next 20 years.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Toward the end of the decade, modern fashion trends began to make its way into country music circles.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] This was specifically inspired by a song, "Harper Valley PTA," written by singer/songwriter Tom T.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Hall about a miniskirt-wearing widowed mother of a teenage girl who was criticized by local school officials for supposedly setting a bad example for her daughter.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The song was recorded by a young secretary named Jeannie C.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Riley, who developed a mod persona in connection with the song by performing onstage in short skirts and go-go boots.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Other female country artists began to follow suit in the years that followed, also appearing onstage in miniskirts and minidresses.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The song reached both the country and pop charts in 1968; and to this day, "Harper Valley PTA" remains the most requested song in Riley's concerts.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] By the late 1960s, Hall began having hits of his own, with songs like "The Ballad Of Forty Dollars" and "Homecoming" both becoming top-10 hits and showcasing his storytelling talents, and that success continued throughout the 1970s and into the 1980s.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] This Brazilian musical style, which means "New Trend", had its origins in the upscale neighbourhoods of Rio de Janeiro.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Immensely popular in the early 1960s, it was a fusion of samba and cool jazz.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Antonio Carlos Jobim, João Gilberto, Astrud Gilberto, and Vinicius de Moraes became some of the best known artists of the Bossa Nova movement.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] The latter's The Girl From Ipanema, released in 1964, became the first Bossa Nova song to achieve international acclaim.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] In 1965, it won a Grammy Award for Best Record of the Year.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Another prominent Latin pop group was Sergio Mendes and Brazil '66.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Their songs included Mas Que Nada, The Joker, and Agua de Beber.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] In 1966 the group was nominated for a Grammy award for Best Performance by a Duo or Musical Group.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] They eventually became Sergio Mendes and Brazil '77, and continued playing their brand of Latin pop into that decade.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Another composer Armando Manzanero widely considered the premier Mexican romantic composer of the postwar era and one of the most successful composers of Latin America has composed more than four hundred songs, fifty of which have given him international fame.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Some renowned trios romantics were Trio Los Panchos, Los Tres Ases, Los Tres Diamantes and Los Dandys.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Trio Bolero, a unique ensemble of two guitars and one cello.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Other singers in singing boleros in Mexico are Óscar Chávez, José Ángel Espinoza and Álvaro Carrillo.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] It was during the 60s that rock music began to gain acclaim in Latin America.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] In Spanish speaking South America musicians who adopted US and British inspired rock, mainly rock and roll, twist and British Invasion music, were collectively labelled as Nueva ola (Spanish for "New Wave").
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Rock music during the 60s was still largely sung in English, but some bands like Los Mac's and others mentioned above used Spanish for their songs as well.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] During the 1960s, most of the music produced in Mexico consisted on Spanish-language versions of English-language rock-and-roll hits.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Singers and musical groups like Angelica Maria, César Costa, Enrique Guzmán performed cover versions of songs by Elvis Presley, Nancy Sinatra, Paul Anka and others.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] During the 1960s Nueva Canción emerges and starts to expand its influence.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] This development is pioneered by the Chileans Violeta Parra and Víctor Jara who base many of their songs in folklore, specially cueca.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Nueva Canción spreads quickly all over Latin America and becomes closely related to the New Left and the Liberation theology movements.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] In Francisco Franco's Spain Joan Manuel Serrat reaches widespread notability as an exponent of Nueva Canción and of the political opposition.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Even though salsa music began to take form in a New York scene dominated by Cubans and other Latin American communities, Salsa would not become popular all across Latin America until the late 1980s and is now here today.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p01] Música cebolla, a style of music loaded with sentimentality, had its heyday in Chile despite being derided or ignored by mass media.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p02] The 1960s saw increasing interest in how electronic music could solve both compositional and more practical problems.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p02] Composers were also absorbing ideas from overseas, such as indeterminacy and electro-acoustic music, and interpreting them in an Australian context to mixed responses from local audiences.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p02] Early in the decade, Bruce Clarke began toying with the new Moog synthesizer.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p02] A musicians' strike led him to create a completely electronic soundtrack for a cigarette commercial in 1963.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p02] Innovative film makers, like Arthur Cantrill and Dušan Marek, employed tape manipulation, turntables and extended instrument techniques to create soundtracks for their short films.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p02] Avowed amateur and Melbourne physician, Val Stephen, became the first Australian to have electronic music released internationally.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p02] After working among the musical avant-garde in Paris, Keith Humble's return to Australia helped to encourage educational institutions to take electronic music seriously.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p02] Humble's most notably experimental work was his Nunique series.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p02] These vast multimedia events featured simultaneous performances by rock bands, string quartets and theatre ensembles, all according to precise flowcharts.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p02] Humble initiated the Melbourne-based Society for the Private Performance of New Music in 1966, providing a supportive performance space for young innovators both in and outside the academy.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p02] Among these were the McKimm/Rooney/Clayton trio, who, since the 1964, had been incorporating graphic scores and aspects of serialism into jazz improvisation.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p02] Jazz was radicalizing at the fringes: John Sangster explored free jazz concepts and Charlie Munro incorporated Eastern musical elements.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p02] Syd Clayton would leave jazz behind in pursuit of a new form of experimental music theatre that incorporated chance operations along with sports and games as musical structures.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p02] Young composers, like David Ahern, emerged, initially inspired by ideas of the European avant-garde, and applying them to Australian icons, such as Captain Cook and Ned Kelly.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p02] Ahern would travel to Europe later in the 1960s, where he encountered Stockhausen and Cardew, before returning home with further more radical ideas that questioned the very premises of composer and music itself.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p02] It is difficult to determine the lasting impact of 1960s music in popular culture.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p02] The song Vivo cantando was joint winner of the Eurovision Song Contest with the United Kingdom's "Boom Bang-a-Bang" performed by Lulu, "De troubadour" by Lenny Kuhr representing the Netherlands, and "Un jour, un enfant" sung for France by Frida Boccara.
[src:african-american-music/1960s-in-music-p02] It was Spain's second winning entry in the contest and the last to date.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] This article includes an overview of the major events and trends in **popular music in the 1970s**.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] In North America, Europe, and Oceania, the decade saw the rise of disco, which then went on to become one of the biggest genres of the decade, especially in the mid-to-late 1970s.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] In Europe, a variant known as Euro disco rose in popularity towards the end of the 1970s.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Aside from disco, funk, soul, R&B, smooth jazz, and jazz fusion remained popular throughout the decade.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Rock music played an important part in the Western musical scene, with punk rock thriving throughout the mid to late 1970s.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Other sub-genres of rock, particularly glam rock, hard rock, progressive rock, art rock, blues rock, and heavy metal achieved various amounts of success.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Other genres such as reggae were innovative throughout the decade and grew a significant following.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Hip hop emerged during this decade, but was slow to start and did not become significant until the late 1980s.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Classical began losing a little momentum; however, through invention and theoretical development, this particular genre gave rise to experimental classical and minimalist music by classical composers.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] A sub-genre of classical, film scores, remained popular with movie-goers.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Its rising popularity, mixed with the popular music of the period, led to the creation of synthpop.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Pop also had a popularity role in the 1970s.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] In Africa, especially Nigeria, the genre known as Afrobeat gained a following throughout the 1970s.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] In Latin America and the Iberian Peninsula, the Nueva canción movement peaked in popularity and was adopted as the music of the hippie, Liberation Theology, and New Left movements.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Cumbia music began its internationalization as regional scenes rose outside Colombia.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Merengue experienced mainstream exposure across Latin America and the southern US border states.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] In Asia, music continued to follow varying trends.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] In Japan, the decade saw several musical trends, including pop music, folk music, rock music and disco music.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Not until 1968 or 1969, when it became a hippie commonplace to dismiss soul as 'commercial' and when bubblegum and 'white blues' developed into clear categories, did the breakdown really begin.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] One of the first events of the 1970s was the break-up of The Beatles in the spring of 1970.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Paul McCartney formed a new group, Wings, and continued to enjoy great mainstream success.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The three other former Beatles — John Lennon, George Harrison, and Ringo Starr — all continued hugely successful recording careers throughout the decade and beyond.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Hard rock and heavy metal gained a cult following in the 1970s, led by Led Zeppelin, Black Sabbath, and Deep Purple, with their styles later influencing other bands like Judas Priest and Motörhead.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] This eventually started the new wave of British heavy metal in the 1980s.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Black Sabbath, formed in 1968 (as The Polka Tulk Blues Band, then Earth), is often credited with inventing the metal genre as well as stoner rock, doom metal, as well as sparking a revolution with much darker lyrics than were the norm in rock at that time.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Progressive or prog rock developed out of late 1960s blues-rock and psychedelic rock.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Dominated by British bands, it was part of an attempt to elevate rock music to new levels of artistic credibility.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Progressive rock bands attempted to push the technical and compositional boundaries of rock by going beyond the standard verse-chorus-based song structures.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The arrangements often incorporated elements drawn from classical, jazz, and world music.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Instrumentals were common, while songs with lyrics were sometimes conceptual, abstract, or based in fantasy.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Progressive rock bands sometimes used "concept albums that made unified statements, usually telling an epic story or tackling a grand overarching theme." King Crimson as well as The Moody Blues have been seen as the bands who established the concept of "progressive rock".
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The term was applied to the music of bands such as Yes, Genesis, Pink Floyd, Jethro Tull, Supertramp and Emerson, Lake & Palmer.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] It reached its peak of popularity in the mid-1970s, but had mixed critical acclaim and the punk movement can be seen as a reaction against its musicality and perceived pomposity.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Nevertheless, Pink Floyd's 1973 release, *The Dark Side of the Moon*, was an immediate success, remaining in the charts for 741 weeks from 1973 to 1988, with an estimated 50 million copies sold.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] It is Pink Floyd's most commercially successful album and one of the best-selling albums worldwide.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] It has twice been remastered and re-released, and has been covered in its entirety by several other acts.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] It spawned two singles, "Money" and "Time".
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] In addition to its commercial success, *The Dark Side of the Moon* is one of Pink Floyd's most popular albums among fans and critics, and is frequently ranked as one of the greatest rock albums of all time.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Glam or glitter rock developed in the UK in the post-hippie early 1970s.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] It was characterized by outrageous clothes, makeup, hairstyles, and platform-soled boots.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The flamboyant lyrics, costumes, and visual styles of glam performers were campy, playing with categories of sexuality in a theatrical blend of nostalgic references to science fiction and old movies, all over a guitar-driven hard rock sound.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Pioneers of the genre included David Bowie, Arrows, Roxy Music, Mott the Hoople, Sparks, Marc Bolan, and T.Rex.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] These, and many other acts straddled the divide between pop and rock music, managing to maintain a level of respectability with rock audiences, while enjoying success in the singles chart, including Queen and Elton John.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Other performers aimed much more directly for the popular music market, where they were the dominant groups of their era, including Slade, Sweet, and Mud.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Largely confined to the British, glam rock peaked during the mid-1970s, before it disappeared in the face of punk rock and new wave trends.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] From the late 1960s it became common to divide mainstream rock music into soft rock and hard rock.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Soft rock was often derived from folk rock, using acoustic instruments and putting more emphasis on melody and harmonies.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] It reached its commercial peak in the mid- to late-1970s with acts like the reformed Fleetwood Mac, whose *Rumours* (1977) was the best-selling album of the decade.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Major British soft rock artists of the 1970s included 10cc, Mungo Jerry, the Hollies, Rod Stewart, the Alan Parsons Project, and Paul McCartney and Wings.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Some of the most successful singers and songwriters were Cat Stevens, Steve Winwood, Albert Hammond, Rupert Holmes, and Elton John.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The mid-1970s saw the rise of punk music from its protopunk-garage band roots in the 1960s and early 1970s.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The Sex Pistols and The Clash were some of the earliest British acts to make it big in both the United Kingdom and the United States.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Groups like the Clash were noted for the experimentation of style, especially that of having strong ska influences in their music.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Punk music has also been heavily associated with a certain punk fashion and absurdist humour which exemplified a genuine suspicion of mainstream culture and values.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The Sex Pistols caused a major sensation in 1977 and were the first serious challenge to the established rock groups like the Rolling Stones and Led Zeppelin, although the punk era in Britain lasted only three years and effectively ended with the Pistols' breakup.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Other European soft rock major artists of the decade included Cat Stevens, Fleetwood Mac, and Joan Armatrading.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] One of the most successful European groups of the decade, and one of the best-selling acts with 380 million records sold, was the quartet ABBA.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The most successful Swedish group of all time, ABBA first found fame when they won the 1974 Eurovision Song Contest.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] They became one of the most widely known European groups ever, as well as Queen promo 1970s.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] "Waterloo", "Mamma Mia", "Take a Chance on Me", "Knowing Me, Knowing You", "Dancing Queen", and "The Winner Takes It All" are just some of ABBA's most popular and most successful songs.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] In the late 1970s, many bands in the United Kingdom began experimenting with synthesizers, forming the new wave style known as synthpop.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Major synthpop bands around this time included Gary Numan and Tubeway Army, the Buggles, the Human League, and Orchestral Manoeuvres in the Dark.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Other successful British new wave bands in the late 1970s included the Police, Echo & the Bunnymen, Adam and the Ants, Roxy Music, Squeeze, XTC, the Cure, the Stranglers, Joy Division, and Siouxsie and the Banshees.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The Bee Gees were one of, if not the 1970s biggest musical act dominating album sales, singles sales and music charts of many countries including the U.S. and UK.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] They were leaders in the disco and pop music scenes of the 1970s; at one point, according to Barry Gibb, they had five songs in the top 10 of the U.S.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] *Billboard* charts at the same time, three of those being in the top 5.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] They were the main writers and performers of the soundtrack to *Saturday Night Fever* which with over 50 million copies worldwide became the second biggest-selling soundtrack of all time, and was the biggest-selling album of all time until Michael Jackson's *Thriller* surpassed it.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Some critics have labeled the Bee Gees as the decade-defining act of the 1970s.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Along with disco, funk was one of the most popular genres of music in the 1970s.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Primarily an African-American genre, it was characterized by the heavy use of bass and "wah-wah" pedals.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Artists such as James Brown, Wilson Pickett, the Meters, Parliament-Funkadelic and Sly and the Family Stone pioneered the genre.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] It then spawned artists such as Stevie Wonder, Rufus, the Brothers Johnson, Kool & the Gang, Chic, Earth, Wind & Fire, the Spinners, King Floyd, Tower of Power, Ohio Players, the Commodores, War, Confunkshun, Gap Band, Slave, Cameo, the Bar-Kays, Zapp, and many more.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Other popular artists in the mainstream were Bill Withers, Gladys Knight & the Pips, Three Dog Night, the Stylistics, the Fifth Dimension, Marvin Gaye, the Temptations, the O'Jays, Barry White and Issac Hayes.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The 1970s saw African-American audiences shift away from genres like rock and blues which had originally been invented and dominated by black musicians.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] King and Albert King remained successful, they changed to a mostly white audience.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Soul, R&B, and funk became the predominant music styles among black artists and audiences.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Roberta Flack had two of the biggest hits of the decade with "The First Time Ever I Saw Your Face", from the Clint Eastwood film *Play Misty for Me*; and "Killing Me Softly".
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Both were #1 hits on the pop charts and she became the first and the only female artist to win back to back Grammy Awards for Record of the Year.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Stevie Wonder who topped the charts five times during the decade with songs such as "You Are the Sunshine of My Life" and "Sir Duke" had a unique treble.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] He won Grammy Awards for both Best Male Pop and Best Male R&B Vocal Performance in 1974, 1975 and 1977.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The Jackson 5 became one of the biggest pop-music phenomena of the 1970s, playing from a repertoire of rhythm and blues, pop and later disco.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The Jacksons — brothers Jackie, Tito, Jermaine, Marlon and Michael — were the first act in recording history to have their first four major label singles, "I Want You Back", "ABC", "The Love You Save" and "I'll Be There" reach the top of the *Billboard* Hot 100.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The band served as the launching pad for the solo careers of their lead singers Jermaine and Michael, who both had some solo success in the early part of the decade; Jermaine with the top 10 hit "Daddy's Home" and Michael who topped the charts with "Ben".
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Other family acts included Gladys Knight & the Pips who topped the charts with "Midnight Train to Georgia", and Sly & the Family Stone who brought "Thank You (Falettinme Be Mice Elf Agin)" and "Family Affair" to the top spot.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Other groups who had hits include the Staple Singers with "I'll Take You There" and "Let's Do It Again", the theme song to a 1975 Sidney Poitier/Bill Cosby film, the Sylvers with "Boogie Fever" and the Emotions with "Best of My Love".
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Honey Cone had a chart-topping hit with "Want Ads", as did Labelle with "Lady Marmalade" and A Taste of Honey with "Boogie Oogie Oogie".
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Other successful girl groups were Love Unlimited and the Three Degrees who scored a U.S.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] 1 hit with "When Will I See You Again" as well as the U.S.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] 1 "TSOP (The Sound of Philadelphia)" with Mother Father Sister Brother (MFSB).
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The Commodores were another group that played from a diverse repertoire, including R&B, funk, and pop.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Lionel Richie, who went on to even greater success as a solo artist in the 1980s, fronted the group's biggest 1970s hits, including "Easy", "Three Times a Lady", and "Still".
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] One of the first disco singer to cross the mainstream was Monti Rock III, with his band, Disco Tex & His Sex-O-Lettes, making "Get Dancin'" and "I Wanna Dance Wit Choo (Doo Dat Dance)".
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Some of the more notable pop/soft rock groups during the 1970s were the Carpenters, the Jackson 5, Seals & Crofts, the Bee Gees, the Doobie Brothers, Hall & Oates, Bread, Captain & Tennille, Tony Orlando and Dawn, Bay City Rollers, and the Osmonds.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Male soloists who characterized the pop music of the era included Barry Manilow, Andy Gibb, Elvis Presley, Neil Diamond, Paul McCartney, Stevie Wonder, Elton John, Marvin Gaye, Cat Stevens, James Taylor, Eric Clapton, Barry White, Dan Hill and Rod Stewart.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Female soloists who epitomized the 1970s included Linda Ronstadt, Carly Simon, Roberta Flack, Donna Summer, Barbra Streisand, Rita Coolidge, Olivia Newton-John, and Helen Reddy.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Some of the most popular music acts of the day got their own network television variety shows, which were very popular in the '70s.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Acts like Sonny & Cher, Glen Campbell, John Denver, Tony Orlando and Dawn, husband and wife team Captain & Tennille, brother and sister Donny & Marie Osmond.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Soft rock was prominently featured on many top 40 and contemporary hit radio stations throughout the 1970s.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Soft rock often used acoustic instruments and placed emphasis on melody and harmonies.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Major soft rock artists of the 1970s included Carole King, James Taylor, Billy Joel, Chicago, America, the Eagles, The Kelly Family and Fleetwood Mac, whose *Rumours* (1977) was the best-selling album of the decade.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Dylan also released some of his most acclaimed albums during the 1970s including *Blood On The Tracks* and *Desire*.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] King's album *Tapestry* became one of the top-selling albums of the decade, and the song "It's Too Late" became one of the 1970s biggest songs.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] McLean's 1971 song "American Pie", inspired by the death of Buddy Holly, became one of popular music's most-recognized songs of the 20th century, thanks to its abstract and vivid storytelling, which center around "The Day the Music Died" and popular music of the rock era.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The early 1970s marked the departure of Diana Ross from the Supremes and the break-up of Simon & Garfunkel and the Beatles.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] All continued hugely successful recording careers throughout the decade.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Some of their songs that are among the hits of the early 1970s: Simon & Garfunkel's "Bridge Over Troubled Water", Simon's solo hit "50 Ways to Leave Your Lover", Paul McCartney's "Uncle Albert/Admiral Halsey", George Harrison's "My Sweet Lord", and Ross' "Ain't No Mountain High Enough".
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Popular British acts were the Rolling Stones, Peter Frampton, Gilbert O'Sullivan, Leo Sayer, the Bee Gees, Queen, Led Zeppelin, Supertramp, and the Who; whose lead singer Roger Daltrey made a splash in the 1975 film *Tommy*, playing the title role, based on the group's 1969 album of the same name.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Elton John, Tina Turner, Ann-Margret, Oliver Reed, Jack Nicholson, and the other band members made up the ensemble cast.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The Ramones, Patti Smith, and Blondie were some of the earliest American punk rock acts to make it big in both the United Kingdom and the United States.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Blondie quickly lost their punk roots, going on to become a pop/ska/reggae band.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The 1970s saw the emergence of hard rock as one of the most prominent subgenres of rock music.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] During the first half of the decade, British acts such as Deep Purple, Led Zeppelin, Uriah Heep and Black Sabbath were at the height of their international fame, particularly in the United States.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] By the second half of the decade, many other acts had also achieved stardom, namely, Mountain, Grand Funk Railroad, Alice Cooper, Cactus, James Gang, AC/DC, Blue Öyster Cult, Kiss, Aerosmith, Van Halen, and Ted Nugent.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Arena rock grew in popularity through rock acts such as Boston, Kansas, Styx, Journey, Toto, Foreigner, and Heart, and the Carpenters.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Psychedelic rock declined in popularity after the deaths of Jimi Hendrix, Janis Joplin and Jim Morrison of the Doors, the self-imposed seclusion of Syd Barrett from Pink Floyd, and the break-up of the Beatles in 1970.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The American brand of prog rock varied from the eclectic and innovative Frank Zappa, Captain Beefheart, Blood, Sweat and Tears, and Rush, to more pop rock oriented bands like Boston, Foreigner, Journey, Kansas, and Styx.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Successful American new wave bands in the late seventies included Talking Heads, the Cars, the Knack, the B-52's, and Devo.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Some of the Canadian new wave groups included Rough Trade, the Payolas, and Martha and the Muffins.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] After the success of British synthpop acts in the U.S. such as Gary Numan and the Buggles, a number of American bands also began experimenting with synthesizers.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] In the early 1980s, bands from the United Kingdom became immensely popular in the U.S., and this phenomenon became known as the Second British Invasion which mainly consisted of British new wave and synthpop acts, therefore broadening the definition of "new wave".
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Blues rock remains popular, with Eric Clapton, ZZ Top, and George Thorogood seeing the greatest success.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Freddie King started moving from straight blues to blues rock since the genre was now mostly popular among white audiences.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Stress from nonstop touring resulted in his death at the age of 42 in 1976.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] A number of styles defined country music during the 1970s decade.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] At the beginning of the decade, the countrypolitan — an offshoot of the earlier "Nashville Sound" of the late 1950s and early 1960s — and the honky-tonk fused Bakersfield Sound were some of the more popular styles.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The Bakersfield sound, first popularized in the early 1960s, continued its peak in popularity through artists such as Buck Owens and Merle Haggard.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] But other styles began to emerge during the 1970s.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] One of the more successful styles was "outlaw country", a type of music blending the traditional and honky tonk sounds of country music with rock and blues music, and mixed with the anger of an alienated subculture of the nation during the period.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The leaders of the movement were Waylon Jennings and Willie Nelson, although others associated with the movement were Jerry Jeff Walker, David Allan Coe, Jessi Colter, Tompall Glaser, Gary Stewart, and Billy Joe Shaver.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The efforts of Jennings, Nelson, Colter, and Glaser were encapsulated in the 1976 album *Wanted!
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The 1970s saw the rise of country music groups.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The most successful act by far during the first half of the decade was The Statler Brothers, a Stanton, Virginia-based group that had gotten its start performing with Johnny Cash in the 1960s.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Both groups remained firmly committed to gospel music, but it was with country-pop that they had their most success and the rise in country groups began to take shape.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] In 1979, a third group – the Fort Payne-based band Alabama, the core being cousins Randy Owen, Teddy Gentry, and Jeff Cook, along with drummer Mark Herndon – emerged, releasing the mellow love ballad "I Wanna Come Over"; although only reaching the mid-30s on the country chart, "...
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Over" was a foreshadowing of what was to come for one of the most successful country music groups/bands of all time, with their blend of soft rock and Southern rock (which would be featured on their next single, "My Home's In Alabama," recorded in 1979 and released in January 1980).
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The country pop sound was a successor to the countrypolitan sound of the early 1970s.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] In addition to artists such as Murray and Campbell, several artists who were not initially marketed as country were enjoying crossover success with country audiences through radio airplay and sales.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The most successful of these artists included The Bellamy Brothers, Charlie Rich, John Denver, Olivia Newton-John, Marie Osmond, B.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Newton-John, an Australian pop singer, was named Female Vocalist of the Year by the Country Music Association in 1974, sparking a debate that continues to this day — what is country music?
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The debate continued into 1975, a year where six songs reached No.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] 1 on both the *Billboard* Hot Country Singles and *Billboard* Hot 100 charts.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Things came to a head when, at that year's CMA Awards, Rich — the reigning Entertainer of the Year, and himself a crossover artist — presented the award to his successor, "my good friend, Mr.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] By the later half of the 1970s, Dolly Parton, a highly successful traditional-minded country artist since the late 1960s, mounted a high-profile campaign to crossover to pop music, culminating in her 1977 hit "Here You Come Again", which peaked at No.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] 1 hits, 11 of them came during the 1970s.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Parton, also became the female country music artist to host her own variety show, *Dolly!,* which aired during the 1976–77 season.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Rogers, the former lead singer of The First Edition, followed up a successful career in pop, rock, and folk music by switching to country music.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Like Parton, whom he would record with in the 1980s and thereafter, Rogers enjoyed a long series of successful songs that charted on both the Hot Country Singles and Billboard Hot 100 charts; the first of the lot was "Lucille," a No.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Crystal Gayle, Ronnie Milsap, Eddie Rabbitt, and Linda Ronstadt were some of the other artists who also found success on both the country and pop charts with their records as well.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The most successful female artist in the 1970s was Loretta Lynn, releasing her best-selling album *Coal Miner's Daughter* in 1970.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] She gained a total of seven number one albums, and 20 number one hit singles including her biggest hit single, 1970s "Coal Miner's Daughter," which went on to sell more than 500,000 copies to date.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Several of Lynn's siblings gained national recording contracts, and it was her youngest sister, Crystal Gayle (born Brenda Gail Webb), who would become by far the most successful.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] 1 singles together, including "After the Fire Is Gone." Like Lynn, Twitty had family—in this case, his children—who also recorded and had songs make the top 40 of the Billboard country chart, but none of them had sustained, long-term success.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Besides Lynn-Twitty duet pairing, there were other notable duet pairings during the 1970s, including George Jones and Tammy Wynette.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Married in 1968, the two had their first duet hit together in 1972 with "Take Me" (a remake of Jones' 1965 solo hit), and went on to have three No.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Wynette, meanwhile, remarried to producer and songwriter George Richey, and continued to perform songs in her signature style, alternating between heartbreak and marital difficulty to loyalty and fidelity.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The 1970s continued a trend toward a proliferation of No.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] In 1970, there were 23 songs that reached the top spot on the chart, but by the mid-1970s, more than 40 titles rotated in and out of the top spot for the first time in history.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The trend temporarily reversed itself by the late 1970s, when about 30 to 35 songs reached the pinnacle position of the chart annually.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Country rock, a subgenre of country music formed from the fusion of rock music with country music, gained its greatest commercial success in the 1970s, beginning with non-country artists such as Bob Dylan, Gram Parsons, and The Byrds.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] By the mid-1970s, Linda Ronstadt, along with other newer artists such as Emmylou Harris and The Eagles, were enjoying mainstream success and popularity that continues to this day.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The Eagles themselves emerged as one of the most successful rock acts of all time, producing albums that included *Hotel California* (1976).
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] It was with both country rock and southern rock that Hank Williams Jr., a longtime stalwart of country music, used to resurrect his career.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] By the mid-1970s, several career- and life-changing events shaped his future.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] He began recording and performing with recording artists including Waylon Jennings, Johnny Cash, and Charlie Daniels, and recorded a Southern rock-heavy album showcasing his new style called *Hank Williams Jr. and Friends*.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] On August 8, 1975, Williams was nearly killed in a mountain climbing accident on the Ajax Peak in southwestern Montana; his recovery took two years, and it was thereafter that he adopted his signature look – a beard, sunglasses, and a cowboy hat.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] In 1979, after a string of modestly-performing singles in his new style, he broke through with "Family Tradition," an autobiographical song about his heritage and new musical identity.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Williams went on to become one of country music's top superstars of the 1980s and beyond with his blend of country, rock, Southern rock and blues, and with songs having themes of soul-searching, rebellion, wild living, and political and societal activism.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The decade saw the deaths of several country music performers, many who would come to be regarded as classic stars of the genre.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The year 1975 was a particularly difficult year for the genre, as three key performers – Bob Wills, George Morgan, and Lefty Frizzell—all died within a two-month timespan.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] In 1977, Elvis Presley and Bing Crosby, two performers not directly identified as country but were vastly influential in and/or had substantial successes and fanbases in the genre, died within six weeks of each other.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The decade saw commercial success for blue-eyed soul artists, such as David Bowie who released the successful albums *Young Americans* (1975), which included the number one hit "Fame", and *Station to Station* (1976).
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] In the second half of the decade, a 1950s nostalgia movement prompted the Rockabilly Revival fad.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The Stray Cats led the revival into the early 1980s.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Queen participated through their hit "Crazy Little Thing Called Love".
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Also symbolizing this trend was the hit movie *Grease* in 1978, starring John Travolta and Olivia Newton-John.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Tying in with the nostalgia craze, several stars of the late 1950s and early 1960s successfully revived their careers during the early- to mid-1970s after several years of inactivity.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Two of popular music's most successful artists died within eight weeks of each other in 1977.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Elvis Presley, the best-selling singer of all time, died on August 16, 1977.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Presley's funeral was held at Graceland, on Thursday, August 18, 1977.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Bing Crosby, who sold about half a billion records, died October 14, 1977.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] His single, "White Christmas", remains as the best selling single of all time, confirmed by the Guinness Records.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The early seventies also marked the deaths of rock legends Jim Morrison, Janis Joplin, Jimi Hendrix, gospel great Mahalia Jackson, and Cass Elliot of the Mamas and the Papas.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The decade also saw the plane crash in 1977 in which three members of Lynyrd Skynyrd were killed.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The mid-to-late 1970s Australian band AC/DC became one of the most popular and successful acts in Australia, scoring a string of hits, albums and singles.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] They made their international debut in 1976 with *High Voltage*.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The band quickly became successful outside their home country; the *Highway to Hell* album from 1979 peaked at number 13 on the Kent Music Report Albums Chart and they would continue as one of the most popular rock groups in the world through the following decade.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The Bee Gees were a British group who had moved to Australia which consisted of brothers Barry, Maurice, and Robin Gibb — a successful harmonic act as the 1970s dawned.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Aside from the chart-topping "How Can You Mend a Broken Heart" in 1971, the brothers did not make much impact in the US during the first half of the decade and most of their record sales were in Europe, especially on the continent.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] With the failure of their 1973 album *Life in a Tin Can*, the Bee Gees appeared washed up.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] But in 1975, they rebounded with *Main Course* which added more of a beat to their songs and they began embracing the new disco sound in their next album *Children of the World* (1976).
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The musical film *Saturday Night Fever* (1977) finally propelled the Bee Gees to global superstar status with "Stayin' Alive", "More Than a Woman", and "Night Fever" (from the *Saturday Night Fever* soundtrack).
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The Gibbs' youngest brother, Andy, was a sensation with his own solo career.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] He made occasional appearances with his brothers and had hits with songs such as "I Just Want to Be Your Everything" and "Shadow Dancing".
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Additional top music acts in Australia and New Zealand included Little River Band, Sherbet, Skyhooks, John Paul Young, Marcia Hines, Jon English, Stevie Wright, Richard Clapton, Dragon, Hush, and the Ted Mulry Gang.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] During the 1970s, Japan had the second largest music market in the world.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] 1970s Japanese music included kayōkyoku, idols and new music.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Musical artists in the 1970s included, in particular, Momoe Yamaguchi, Saori Minami, the Candies, Pink Lady, Hiromi Go, Hideki Saijo, Yuming, Saki Kubota, Judy Ongg and Sachiko Kobayashi.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The 1970s in Hong Kong saw the popularization of Cantopop, which developed out of traditional-styled songs used in Cantonese-language soap operas and the influence of British and American soft rock.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Cantopop would become Hong Kong's biggest cultural export, coupled on the popularity of Hong Kong soap operas across the Chinese-speaking world.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Indonesia in the 1970s saw the peak of Indian- and Arab-influenced dangdut, which emerged in the 1960s, and the development of Western-influenced Indo pop.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The Philippines in the early 1970s saw the emergence of Manila sound.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Originally influenced by rock and roll and bubblegum pop, it became more influenced by disco and funk by the second half of the decade.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Original Pilipino music (OPM), mostly sentimental ballads, developed in the mid-1970s and became the dominant form of Filipino pop, helped by government-set local content quotas on radio that begun in 1973.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Old-style sentimental ballads popularized in the 1960s remained popular into the 1970s.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Some major Filipino acts of the decade are Freddie Aguilar, Rico J.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Puno, Rey Valera, APO Hiking Society, Claire dela Fuente, Imelda Papin, Hotdog, Sampaguita and VST & Company.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] 'Child') was an international hit in 1978 and translated into 56 languages.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Jose Jose big break came on 15 March 1970, when he represented Mexico in the international song festival the *II Festival de la Canción Latina* (Latin Song Festival II, predecessor of the OTI Festival) with a performance of the song "El Triste".
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Although José José finished in third place, his performance helped launch his music career to a wider audience.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] In 1971, Juan Gabriel released his first studio album *El Alma Joven...*, which included the song "No Tengo Dinero", which became his debut single and his first hit.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Vicente Fernández's greatest hit was "Volver, volver," released in 1972; his first million-selling album was 1983's 15 Grandes con el número uno.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] During the 1970s in Latin America, the 1960s music influence remained strong and two styles developed from it one that followed the European and North American trends and Nueva Canción that focused on the renewal of folklore including Andean music and cueca.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Some bands such as Los Jaivas from Chile mixed both streams and created a syncretism between folklore and progressive rock.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The Nueva Canción movement got an even more marked protest association after all countries in the Southern Cone became (or were already) military dictatorships in the 1970s.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] In Chile, the Nueva canción styles developed through the 1970s would remain popular until the return to democracy in 1990.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] In the 1970s, rock en Español began to emerge (especially in Argentina), and as imitation bands became fewer, rock music started to develop more independently from the outside, although many rock bands still preferred to sing in English.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The Argentine defeat in the Falklands War in 1982 followed by the fall of the mhilitary junta that year diminished need of Nueva Canción as protest music there in favour of other styles.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Sonora Santanera is an orchestra playing tropical music from Mexico with over 60 years of history.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The Wailers, a band started by Bob Marley, Peter Tosh and Bunny Wailer in 1963 which used to play ska and rocksteady music during the 1960s, became popular in the Caribbean, Europe and Africa since the early 1970s after they started playing reggae music.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Later on, the band became very popular in the US.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The Wailers broke up in 1974 with each of the three main members going on to pursue solo careers.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Despite the break-up, Marley continued recording music under the name Bob Marley & The Wailers.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] In 1975, Marley had his international breakthrough with his first hit outside Jamaica, "No Woman, No Cry", from the *Natty Dread* album.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The success of the album *Exodus* (1977), which included the major international hits "Jamming", "Turn Your Lights Down Low", and "One Love", propelled Marley to international stardom.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] In addition to the Wailers, other significant pioneers include Prince Buster, Desmond Dekker, Jackie Mittoo, and several others.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Fela Anikulapo Kuti, or simply Fela, was a Nigerian human rights activist, political maverick, multi-instrumentalist, musician, and pioneer of the Afrobeat music genre.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] It was during the 1970s the cumbia became widely popular outside Colombia.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Several bands brought Cumbia to Mexico, Peru, Argentina, and Chile places that later became major scenes for further developments of cumbia music.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] Salsa music developed in the 1960s and 1970s by Puerto Rican and Cuban immigrants to the New York City area but did not enter into mainstream popularity in Latin America until the late 1980s.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The merengue music experienced during the late 1970s was a golden age of productivity characterized by the rise of a new generation of musicians.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] The commercial cinemas around the world tended to imitate nuances of disco beats in their movies to present their movies as western and upbeat.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] These included the increasingly popular kung-fu movies in far East Asia and Bollywood movies from India.
[src:african-american-music/1970s-in-music] These trends are essential in proving that commercial cinemas were a beneficial investment for the community.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson's debut studio album, *Get Rich or Die Tryin'* (2003), was released to critical acclaim and commercial success.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Peaking atop the *Billboard* 200, it spawned the *Billboard* Hot 100-number one singles "In da Club" and "21 Questions" (featuring Nate Dogg), and received Multiple Platinum certification by the Recording Industry Association of America (RIAA).
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Also in 2003, he launched the record label G-Unit Records, namesake of a hip-hop group he formed two years earlier; the label's initial signees were its members, fellow East Coast rappers Lloyd Banks and Tony Yayo.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] His second album, *The Massacre* (2005), met with continued success, yielding his third number-one single, "Candy Shop" (featuring Olivia).
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] He has since focused on television and media, having executive-produced and starred in the television series *Power* (2014–2020), as well as its numerous spin-offs under his company G-Unit Films and Television Inc.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson has sold over 30 million albums worldwide and earned several accolades, including a Grammy Award, a Primetime Emmy Award, 13 *Billboard* Music Awards, 6 World Music Awards, 3 American Music Awards, and 4 BET Awards.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] He starred in the semi-autobiographical film *Get Rich or Die Tryin'* (2005), which was critically panned.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] He also appeared in the war film *Home of the Brave* (2006) and the crime thriller *Righteous Kill* (2008).
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] *Billboard* ranked Jackson 17th on its "50 Greatest Rappers" list in 2023, and named him the sixth top artist of the 2000s decade.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] *Rolling Stone* ranked *Get Rich or Die Tryin'* and "In da Club" in its lists of the "100 Best Albums of the 2000s" and "100 Best Songs of the 2000s" at numbers 37 and 13, respectively.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson was born in Queens, New York City, and raised in the South Jamaica neighborhood by his mother, Sabrina.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] A drug dealer, Sabrina raised Jackson until she died in a fire when Jackson was eight years old.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson said in an interview that she was a lesbian.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] After his mother's death and his father's departure, Jackson was raised by his grandparents.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson began boxing at about age 11, and when he was 14, a neighbor opened a boxing gym for local youth.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] "When I wasn't killing time in school, I was sparring in the gym or selling crack on the strip", he has said.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] "I was competitive in the ring and hip-hop is competitive too ...
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] At age 12, Jackson began dealing narcotics when his grandparents thought he was in after-school programs, and brought guns and drug money to school.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In tenth grade, he was caught by metal detectors at Andrew Jackson High School: "I was embarrassed that I got arrested like that ...
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] After I got arrested I stopped hiding it.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] On June 29, 1994, Jackson was arrested for selling four vials of cocaine to an undercover police officer.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] He was arrested again three weeks later when police searched his home and found heroin, ten ounces of crack cocaine, and a starting pistol.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson was sentenced to three to nine years in prison, but served six months in a boot camp and earned his GED.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] He has said that he did not use cocaine himself.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson adopted the nickname "50 Cent" as a metaphor for change.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] The name was inspired by Kelvin Martin, a 1980s Brooklyn robber known as "50 Cent"; Jackson chose it "because it says everything I want it to say.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] I'm the same kind of person 50 Cent was.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson began rapping in a friend's basement, using turntables to record over instrumentals.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In 1996, a friend introduced him to Jam Master Jay of Run-DMC, who was establishing Jam Master Jay Records.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jay taught him to count bars, write choruses, structure songs, and make records.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In 1997, A&R of Def Jam Irv Gotti turned down demo tapes by Jackson that Jay showed him for a potential record deal on the grounds that they were too similar to Jay-Z.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson's first appearance was on "React" with Onyx, from its 1998 album *Shut 'Em Down*, which Gotti was the A&R for.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] He credited Jam Master Jay for improving his ability to write hooks, and Jay produced Jackson's first (unreleased) album.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In 1999, after Jackson left Jam Master Jay, the platinum-selling producers Trackmasters signed him to Columbia Records.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] They sent him to an upstate New York studio, where he produced 36 songs in two weeks; 18 were included on his 2000 album *Power of the Dollar*.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson founded Hollow Point Entertainment with former G-Unit member Bang 'Em Smurf.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson's popularity began to grow after the successful, controversial underground single "How to Rob", which he wrote in a half-hour car ride to a studio.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] The track comically describes how he would rob famous artists.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Although "How to Rob" was intended to be released with "Thug Love" (with Destiny's Child), two days before he was scheduled to film the "Thug Love" video, Jackson was shot and hospitalized.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] On May 24, 2000, Jackson was attacked by a gunman outside his grandmother's former home in South Jamaica.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] After getting into a friend's car, he was asked to return to the house to get some jewelry; his son was in the house, and his grandmother was in the front yard.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson returned to the car, and another car pulled up nearby; an assailant walked up and fired nine shots at close range with a 9mm handgun.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson was shot in the hand, arm, hip, both legs, chest, and left cheek.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] His facial wound resulted in a swollen tongue, the loss of a wisdom tooth and a slightly slurred voice; his friend was wounded in the hand.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] They were driven to a hospital, where Jackson spent 13 days.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] The alleged attacker, Darryl "Homicide" Baum, Mike Tyson's close friend and bodyguard, was killed three weeks later.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson recalled the shooting: "It happens so fast that you don't even get a chance to shoot back ....
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] I was looking in the rear-view mirror like, 'Oh shit, somebody shot me in the face!
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] It burns, burns, burns.'" In his autobiography, *From Pieces to Weight: Once upon a Time in Southside Queens*, he wrote: "After I got shot nine times at close range and didn't die, I started to think that I must have a purpose in life ...
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] How much more damage could that shell have done?
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Give me an inch in this direction or that one, and I'm gone." Jackson used a walker for six weeks and fully recovered after five months.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] When he left the hospital, he stayed in the Poconos with his girlfriend and son, and his workout regime helped him develop a muscular physique.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In the hospital, Jackson signed a publishing deal with Columbia Records before he was dropped from the label and blacklisted by the recording industry because of his song "Ghetto Qu'ran".
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Unable to work in a U.S. studio, he went to Canada.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] With business partner Sha Money XL, Jackson recorded over 30 songs for mixtapes to build a reputation.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In a HitQuarters interview, Marc Labelle of Shady Records A&R said Jackson used the mixtape circuit to his advantage: "He took all the hottest beats from every artist and flipped them with better hooks.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] They then got into all the markets on the mixtapes and all the mixtape DJs were messing with them." Jackson's popularity increased, and in 2002 he released the mixtape *Guess Who's Back?*.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] He then released *50 Cent Is the Future* backed by G-Unit, a mixtape revisiting material by Jay-Z and Raphael Saadiq.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In 2002, Eminem received *Guess Who's Back?* from Jackson's attorney, who was working with Eminem's manager, Paul Rosenberg.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Impressed, Eminem invited Jackson to Los Angeles and introduced him to Dr.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] After signing a $1 million record deal, Jackson released the mixtape *No Mercy, No Fear*.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] It featured one new track, "Wanksta", which appeared on Eminem's *8 Mile* soundtrack.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson was also signed by Violator Management and Sha Money XL's Money Management Group.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson released his debut album, *Get Rich or Die Tryin'* (described by AllMusic as "probably the most hyped debut album by a rap artist in about a decade"), in February 2003.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] *Rolling Stone* noted its "dark synth grooves, buzzy keyboards and a persistently funky bounce", with Jackson complementing the production in "an unflappable, laid-back flow".
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] It debuted at number one on the *Billboard* 200, selling 872,000 copies in its first four days.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] The lead single, "In da Club" (noted by *The Source* for its "blaring horns, funky organs, guitar riffs and sparse hand claps"), set a *Billboard* record as the most listened-to song in radio history within a week.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Interscope began funding and distributing for Jackson's label, G-Unit Records, in 2003.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] He signed Lloyd Banks, Tony Yayo, and Young Buck as members of G-Unit, and The Game was later signed in a joint venture with Dr.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] G-Unit Records replaced Jackson's previous imprint, Rotten Apple Entertainment.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] 50 Cent executive produced Lloyd Banks's 2004 debut studio album, *The Hunger for More*, which achieved platinum status in the U.S.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson also contributed vocals to Banks's hit single "On Fire".
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In March 2005, Jackson's second commercial album, *The Massacre*, sold 1.14 million copies in its first four days (the highest in an abbreviated sales cycle) and was number one on the *Billboard* 200 for six weeks.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] He was the first solo artist with three singles in the *Billboard* top five in the same week with "Candy Shop", "Disco Inferno" and "How We Do".
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] According to *Rolling Stone*, "50's secret weapon is his singing voice—the deceptively amateur-sounding tenor croon that he deploys on almost every chorus".
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson's video game, *50 Cent: Bulletproof* was released in November 2005.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] He portrays himself and provides his likeness and voice in the game, which features music from his first two studio albums.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] After The Game's departure, Jackson signed Olivia and rap veterans Mobb Deep to G-Unit Records, and later Spider Loc, M.O.P., 40 Glocc, and Young Hot Rod.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson expressed interest in working with rappers other than G-Unit, such as Lil' Scrappy of BME, LL Cool J of Def Jam, Mase of Bad Boy, and Freeway of Roc-A-Fella, and recorded with several.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In September 2007, Jackson released his third album, *Curtis*, inspired by his life before *Get Rich or Die Tryin'*.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] It debuted at number two on the *Billboard* 200, selling 691,000 copies during its first week.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] It sold behind Kanye West's *Graduation*, released the same day; the outcome of this highly publicized sales battle between Jackson and West has been accredited to the commercial decline of the gangsta rap and "bling era" style that previously dominated mainstream hip-hop.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In 2008, 50 Cent co-signed the underground rap group Bang Bang Boogie, which consisted of Mysonne, Cuban Link, Lord Tariq, Hocus 45th and S-One, giving them his stamp of approval.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] The group released the mixtapes *The Machine, Vol.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] 1* and *X-Files: No Mercy For The Weak* in that same year before disbanding shortly due to Hocus and S-One being falsely incarcerated for gang-related crimes.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] The group was known for representing The Bronx and for their beef with Fat Joe as they dissed him on songs such as "High Blood Pressure" and "Bang Out".
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] On September 10, 2008, episode of *Total Request Live,* Jackson said his fourth studio album, *Before I Self Destruct*, would be "done and released in November".
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] He released "Ok, You're Right", produced by Dr.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Dre for *Before I Self Destruct*, on May 18, 2009, and was scheduled to appear in a fall 2009 episode of VH1's *Behind the Music*.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] On September 3, 2009, Jackson posted a video for the Soundkillers' Phoenix- produced track, "Flight 187", introducing his mixtape and book (*The 50th Law*).
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] The song, with lyrics inspiring speculation about tension between Jackson and Jay-Z, was a bonus track on the iTunes version of *Before I Self Destruct*.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] *Before I Self Destruct* was released on November 9, 2009, and debuted at number 5 on the *Billboard 200*, giving 50 Cent his fourth consecutive top 5 album in the U.S.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In a Contactmusic.com interview, Jackson said he was working on a Eurodance album, *Black Magic*, inspired by European nightclubs: "First they played hip-hop which suddenly changed to uptempo songs, known as Eurodance".
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] He later said he had changed his next album to *The Return of the Heartless Monster* after writing different material when he returned home from the Invitation Tour in 2010, shelving *Black Magic*.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] On September 3, Jackson supported Eminem on his and Jay-Z's The Home & Home Tour, performing "Crack A Bottle" with Eminem and Dr.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Dre amid rumors of tension between Jackson and Dre.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] He "recorded 20 songs to a whole different album concept" before putting them aside, wanting his new album to have the "aggression" of *Get Rich or Die Tryin'*.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson tweeted that the album was "80 percent done" and fans could expect it in the summer of 2011.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] It was ultimately delayed a year due to disagreements with Interscope Records, with Jackson saying that he would release it in November 2011 with a different title than *Black Magic*.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Eminem would appear on the album, and Jackson said he was working with new producers such as Boi-1da and Alex da Kid.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Cardiak, who produced Lloyd Banks's "Start It Up", confirmed that he produced a song for the album.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson released a song, "Outlaw", from his fifth album online on June 16, 2011.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] The single, produced by Cardiak, was released on iTunes on July 19 (although Jackson tweeted that it was not the album's first single).
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson planned to write a semi-autobiographical young-adult novel about bullying, different from his previous books, which focused on his life and the rules of power.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] According to the book's publisher, the first-person novel (about a 13-year-old schoolyard bully "who finds redemption as he faces what he's done") was scheduled for publication in January 2012.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In a series of tweets, Jackson said that the delay of his fifth album was due to disagreements with Interscope Records, later suggesting that it would be released in November 2011 with his headphone line (SMS by 50).
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] He speculated to MTV News about not renewing his five-album contract with Interscope: "I don't know ...
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] It will all be clear in the negotiations following me turning this actual album in.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] On June 20, 2011, Jackson announced the release of *Before I Self Destruct II* after his fifth album.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Although he planned to shoot a video for the album's lead single, "I'm On It", on June 26, it was never filmed.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson told Shade45, "I did four songs in Detroit with Eminem.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] I did two with Just Blaze, a Boi-1da joint, and I did something with Alex da Kid.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] An announcement that Jackson was shooting a video for "Girls Go Wild", the fifth-album lead single featuring Jeremih, was made on September 28, 2011.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson's fifth album, *Street King Immortal*, was first scheduled for a summer 2012 release but postponed to November 13.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Disagreements with Interscope Records about its release and promotion led to its temporary cancellation.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Its first promo single, "New Day" with Dr.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Dre and Alicia Keys, was released on July 27.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Dre, mixed by Eminem, and written by 50 Cent, Alicia Keys, Royce da 5'9" and Dr.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] A solo version by Keys was leaked by her husband, Swizz Beatz.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] "My Life", the album's second promo single (with Eminem and Maroon 5 lead singer Adam Levine), was released on November 26, 2012.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In January 2014, Jackson said he planned to release *Animal Ambition* in the first quarter of the year, followed by *Street King Immortal*.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] On February 20, he left Shady Records, Aftermath Entertainment, and Interscope, signing with Caroline and Capitol Music Group.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] According to Jackson, although he owed Interscope another album, he was released from his contract because of his friendship with Eminem and Dr.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] It's also because of the leverage of having the strong relationships with Eminem and Dr.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] That day, he announced that *Animal Ambition* would be released on June 3 and released its first track.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] The song, "Funeral", was released with a video on Forbes.com.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Produced by Jake One, it is a continuation of "50 Bars" from a previous album; two more tracks were scheduled for release on March 18.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] At South by Southwest, Jackson performed "Hold On" from the new album.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] That song and "Don't Worry 'Bout It" were released with accompanying videos on March 18.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] According to Jackson, prosperity would be a theme of the album: "This project, I had to search for a concept, a really good concept, in my perspective, and that was prosperity.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] On May 14, 2015, Jackson said in an interview that the first single from *Street King Immortal* would be previewed on Memorial Day weekend and likely be released in June.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] He released "Get Low" on May 20 as the intended first single from his sixth studio album, *Street King Immortal*.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] The song, produced by Remo the Hitmaker, features vocals from 2 Chainz, T.I., and Jeremih.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] He announced bankruptcy on July 13, 2015.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] On March 31, 2017, Interscope Records released 50 Cent's final album for the label, the greatest-hits album *Best Of*.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In 2019, 50 Cent was featured on English singer-songwriter Ed Sheeran's fourth studio album, No.6 Collaborations Project with American rapper Eminem, on "Remember the Name".
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In 2020, Jackson stepped in as executive producer for late rapper Pop Smoke's debut album, *Shoot for the Stars, Aim for the Moon*, having been one of Pop Smoke's biggest inspirations.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] The album was released on July 3, 2020, to nationwide commercial acclaim.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson curated the album, desiring to finish it after Pop had died.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] He contacted many of the artists involved, and also features on one of the album tracks, "The Woo".
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] The Woo also features vocals by Roddy Ricch.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In 2020, it was reported that Jackson was producing two television series for Starz, an anthology about hip-hop and a biographical drama about sports agent Nicole Lynn.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In 2021, he became one of the headliners of the music festival *Golden Sand* in Riviera Maya.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In a July 2021 interview with *The Independent*, 50 Cent said he had decided to shelve his *Street King Immortal* album after it spent a decade in development hell and planned to release a completely new project.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] This was thought to be for lower taxes, no income tax, the rapper scene, and other ventures such as writing new screenplays.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson, Horizon United Group, and Houston Independent School District began a partnership on a project to help high school students learn the business skills.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] While living in Houston, Jackson worked on screenplays for new crime shows.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In August 2021, he was confirmed to be starring in the film *Expend4bles*; it was released on September 22, 2023.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] The film was a critical and commercial failure, grossing $51 million against a $100 million production budget.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson is the executive producer of the show.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] He also performed the show's theme song, "Wish Me Luck", alongside Charlie Wilson, Moneybagg Yo, and Snoop Dogg.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] On February 13, 2022, 50 Cent was a surprise performer in the Super Bowl LVI halftime show, receiving a Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Variety Special (Live) in September for the performance.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] From December 2024 to January 2025, Jackson embarked on his Las Vegas residency, *50 Cent: In da Club*, which had been announced in October.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] He also announced plans to executive-produce *Sean Combs: The Reckoning* for Netflix, a documentary centered on the sexual misconduct allegations against hip-hop entrepreneur Sean Combs.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In January 2025, *Den of Thieves 2: Pantera* was released as a sequel to the 2018 film.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson, who starred in the 2018 film, executive produced the sequel alongside former co-star O'Shea Jackson Jr., who reprised his role.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson cites Boogie Down Productions, Big Daddy Kane, The Juice Crew, EPMD and KRS-One as his rapping influences, while citing LL Cool J as an inspiration behind his writing of "21 Questions".
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] He has also said he was influenced by Nas, Rakim, and The Notorious B.I.G. while working on *Animal Ambition*.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson has had a highly successful business career.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] He is financially invested in a highly diversified variety of industries.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson is now involved in artist and talent management, record, television, and film production, footwear, apparel, fragrances, liquor, video games, mobile apps, book publishing, headphones, along with health drinks and dietary supplements.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] His broad business and investment portfolio contains investments in a variety of sectors including real estate, financial market investments, mining, boxing promotion, vodka, fragrances, consumer electronics and fashion.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] He established his own record label G-Unit Records in 2003 following his mainstream success.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In November 2003, he signed a five-year deal with Reebok to distribute a G-Unit Sneakers line for his G-Unit Clothing Company.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In an interview, Jackson said his businesses had a habit of doing well as he saw all of his ventures both past and present as revolving around his alter ego.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson has also started a book publishing imprint, G-Unit Books on January 4, 2007, at the Time Warner Building in New York.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] He has written a number of books including a memoir, *From Pieces To Weight* in 2005 which sold 73,000 copies in hardcover and 14,000 copies in paperback; a crime novel and a book with Robert Greene titled *The 50th Law*, an urban take on *The 48 Laws of Power*.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In November 2011, Jackson released *50 Cent's Playground*, a young adult fiction novel about a bullied, violent boy and his gay mother.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] One of Jackson's first business ventures was a partnership with Glacéau to create an enhanced water drink called Formula 50.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In October 2004, Jackson became a beverage investor when he was given a minority share in the company in exchange for becoming a spokesperson after learning that he was a fan of the beverage.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] The health conscious Jackson noted that he first learned of the product while at a gym in Los Angeles, and stated that "they do such a good job making water taste good".
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] After becoming a minority shareholder and celebrity spokesperson, Jackson worked with the company to create a new grape flavored "Formula 50" variant of VitaminWater and mentioned the drinks in various songs and interviews.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In 2007, Coca-Cola purchased Glacéau for $4.1 billion and, according to *Forbes*, Jackson, a minority shareholder, earned $100 million from the deal after taxes.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Though he no longer has an equity stake in the company, Jackson continues to act as a spokesperson for VitaminWater, supporting the product including singing about it at the BET Awards and expressing his excitement that the company continues to allow his input on products.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] He joined Right Guard to introduce a body spray (Pure 50 RGX) and endorsed Magic Stick condoms, planning to donate part of their proceeds to increasing HIV awareness.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson signed a multi-year deal with Steiner Sports to sell his memorabilia, and announced plans for a dietary-supplement company in conjunction with his film *Spectacular Regret* in August 2007.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson has founded two film production companies: G-Unit Films in 2003 and Cheetah Vision in 2008.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Cheetah Vision produces low-budget action thrillers for foreign film markets across the world.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] When G-Unit Films folded, he focused on Cheetah Vision and the company obtained $200 million in funding in 2010.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In 2010, Jackson revived G-Unit Films, renaming it G-Unit Film and Television, Inc.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] The company had joint ventures with Will Packer's production company, Will Packer Productions, and Universal Television.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In over 18 months, Jackson sold projects to six different television networks.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Kemp-created *Power*, a crime drama in which he co-starred as Kanan Stark and served as an executive producer.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] *Power* debuted on Starz on June 7, 2014, and ended on February 9, 2020, after six seasons.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] He signed a two-year contract with representation from the Agency for the Performing Arts.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Ratings have been a success for Starz, with the second-season premiere being the highest with 1.43 million viewers.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson is also the executive producer of three of the series' spin-offs, *Power Book II: Ghost*, *Power Book III: Raising Kanan* and *Power Book IV: Force*.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Offices for G-Unit Film and Television (also known as G-Unit Studios) are headquartered in Shreveport, Louisiana, as part of a 45-year lease agreement with the state.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In 2002, Jackson filed an application with the United States Patent and Trademark Office to register the term "50 Cent" as a trademark for clothing, sound recordings, and live performances.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] The application was published in 2003, and registration issued in 2004.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] He has since filed for additional trademark registrations.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In July 2011, Jackson launched a philanthropic initiative to provide food for one billion starving people in Africa by 2016, joining Pure Growth Partners to introduce Street King.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] A portion of the proceeds from each Street King purchase would be used to provide a daily meal to an underprivileged child.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] The partnership coincides with Jackson's goal to feed a billion people in Africa during the next five years.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] "50 Cent and I share a common vision: to address the world's problems through smart and sustainable business models," said Chris Clarke, founder and CEO of Pure Growth Partners.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] "With the rampant starvation in Africa and hunger afflicting children worldwide, we need socially responsible businesses that affect real change now more than ever." Jackson said, "I'm inspired by Clarke's vision and innovative approaches to tackling serious issues.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] It's our mission with Street King to really change children's lives around the world." In 2011, he founded SMS Audio, a consumer-electronics company selling Street by 50 headphones, pledging to donate a portion of their sales to charity.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In April 2015, SMS announced new co-branding deals with Reebok and Marvel.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] It added those to existing partnerships with Walt Disney Parks, Lucasfilm's Star Wars, and Intel.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In 2014, Jackson became a minority shareholder in Effen Vodka, a brand of vodka produced in the Netherlands, when he invested undisclosed amount in the company, Sire Spirits, LLC.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] He endorsed the product via his live concert performances and social media.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] The rapper was asked to take part in two promotional bottle signings, one in Oak Creek and another in Sun Prairie.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson made an appearance at Liquor Warehouse in Syracuse, New York on April 25, 2015, where he reportedly sold 1,400 bottles (277 gallons) of Jackson's signature liquor brand.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Liquor Warehouse's owner, George Angeloro, reportedly stocked 300 cases (1,800 bottles or 357 gallons) of Effen Vodka, which sells for $30 a bottle, prior to the event.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In December 2014, Jackson signed a $78 million deal with FRIGO Revolution Wear, a luxury underwear brand.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] The joint venture is partnered between Jackson, basketball player Carmelo Anthony, baseball player Derek Jeter and Mathias Ingvarsson, the former president of mattress company Tempur-Pedic.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson became the chief fashion designer for the brands single pair of Frigo boxers.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In April 2015, Jackson mulled investing in Jamaica, exploring foreign investment opportunities on the island when he met with some local officials and had ongoing discussions on investment opportunities in the Montego Bay resort area.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Over the years, Jackson invested his earnings from music and celebrity endorsements in an array of privately controlled companies, real estate, and stocks and bonds.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] A portion of his investments lost value during the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In December 2008, he told the Canadian press that he had been affected by the recession, losing several million dollars in the stock market.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Unable to sell his Connecticut mansion, Jackson postponed *Before I Self-Destruct* due to the severity of the economic downturn.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] His Farmington mansion at 50 Poplar Hill Drive that he tried to sell for years filed for bankruptcy in Connecticut in 2015.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Its asking price in 2012 was $10 million but it was valued at $8.3 million in 2015.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] He first tried to sell the house in 2007 for $18.5 million, and dropped the price several times in the next five years, when it was on and off the market.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In January 2011, Jackson reportedly made $10 million after using Twitter to promote a marketing company of which he was a shareholder.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] His endorsements company G Unit Brands Inc. controlled 12.9% of H&H Imports, a parent company of TV Goods, the firm responsible for marketing his range of headphones, Sleek by 50 Cent.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson bought stock in the company on November 30, 2010, a week after it offered buyers 180 million shares at $0.17 each.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson later made a stock recommendation on Twitter, causing its share price to rise from $0.04 to nearly $0.50, closing on Monday at $0.39.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson was later investigated by the Securities and Exchange Commission for breaching securities laws, as his tweet may have constituted insider trading with a pump and dump investment strategy.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In 2013, Jackson became a minority investor in Hang w/, a live video broadcasting mobile app used by dozens of celebrities to broadcast their daily activities and chat with fans.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] The app was downloaded more than 1 million times after launching in March 2013 and had more than 1 million users as of February 2015.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Other minority celebrity investors were former NFL player Terrell Owens and record producer Timbaland.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In 2008, Jackson visited a platinum, palladium and iridium mine shaft in South Africa, and met with South African billionaire Patrice Motsepe in talks of purchasing an equity stake in the mine.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] After meeting with Motsepe, Jackson considered purchasing equity in the mine and launching his own line of 50 Cent branded platinum.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] On July 21, 2012, Jackson became a licensed boxing promoter when he formed his new company, TMT (The Money Team).
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Licensed to promote in New York, he was in the process of being licensed in Nevada (where most major fights are held in the U.S.).
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] A former amateur boxer, Jackson signed gold medalist and former featherweight champion Yuriorkis Gamboa and middleweight Olympic medalist Andre Dirrell.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] On July 29, he and the boxer Floyd Mayweather Jr. signed IBF featherweight champion Billy Dib.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] They unveiled plans to challenge the box-office dominance of mixed martial arts and change the landscape of boxing with TMT Promotions.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Boxer Zab Judah also expressed interest in making a deal with Jackson.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In December, Mayweather and Jackson parted company, with Jackson taking over the promotion company and founding SMS Promotions with Gamboa, Dirrell, Dib, James Kirkland, Luis Olivares, and Donte Strayhorn in his stable.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] On July 13, 2015, Jackson filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection in the U.S.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Bankruptcy Court for the District of Connecticut with a debt of $32,509,549.91.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] On July 17, the Court issued an order allowing a creditor to proceed with the punitive damages phase of a trial against Jackson in a New York state court in connection with the alleged release of a private video.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] His assets were listed as between $10 million and $50 million in his bankruptcy petition, though he testified under oath that he was worth $4.4 million.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] He said that he had between $10 million and $50 million in debt and the same amount in assets.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Later in the week, Jackson's bankruptcy lawyers elucidated through the court documents that legal fees and judgments exceeding $20 million over the past year were the primary cause of the filing.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] His filings listed 32 entities in which he had a stake.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] The bankruptcy came days after a jury ordered him to pay $5 million to Rick Ross's ex-girlfriend Lastonia Leviston for invading her privacy by posting online a sex tape of her and another man.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In addition, Jackson lost a dispute over a failed business deal involving his Sleek headphones, where Jackson invested more than $2 million.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] An ex-partner accused Jackson of stealing the design of the "Sleek by 50" headphones, prompting a judge to award the partner more than $17.2 million.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] His Connecticut bankruptcy filing stated that he owned seven cars valued at more than $500,000, including a 2010 Rolls-Royce and a 1966 Chevrolet Coupe.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] His monthly expenses of $108,000 included $5,000 for gardening.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] He reported a monthly income of $185,000, mainly from royalties and his external businesses and investments.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] The court filing said he also owed money to his stylist, his barber, and his fitness coach.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Other details in the bankruptcy documents included information about two deals that sold the right to collect royalties of on-air play of his music.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Half the rights to his portfolio were sold to the British independent music publishing company Kobalt Music Group for $3 million and the other half for another $3 million, with the sales of his albums allowing Jackson to own the rights to the master recordings while paying only for distribution.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Zeisler & Zeisler, a Bridgeport law firm, represented 50 Cent in the bankruptcy, which resulted in Jackson filing a $75 million lawsuit against his own lawyers.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] He said his lawyers did a terrible job of representing him, specifically citing the fallout of his failed venture with Sleek Audio headphones.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] He accused Garvey Schubert Barer, a Wall Street law firm, of failing to "employ the requisite knowledge and skill necessary to confront the circumstances of the case".
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] 50 Cent has said his life philosophy since his shooting has been "When your time comes, you go.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] I think that comes from God." Despite numerous songs that reference drug and alcohol use and his ownership of Branson Cognac, Jackson remains a teetotaler, citing a bad experience with alcohol as his main reason.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] The mayor of Bridgeport, Connecticut, declared October 12, 2007 "50 Cent Curtis Jackson Day", honoring him with a proclamation and a key to the city.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] One of Jackson's New York homes, purchased in January 2007 for $2.4 million and the center of a lawsuit between Jackson and Shaniqua Tompkins, caught fire on May 31, 2008, while he was filming in Louisiana.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] On October 13, 1997, Jackson's girlfriend, Shaniqua Tompkins, gave birth to son Marquise.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In 2009 Tompkins sued Jackson for $50 million, saying he promised to take care of her for life.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] The suit, with 15 causes of action, was dismissed by a judge who called it "an unfortunate tale of a love relationship gone sour".
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] The two have had a dispute for years and taken it to social media many times.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Marquise's birth changed Jackson's outlook on life: "When my son came into my life, my priorities changed, because I wanted to have the relationship with him that I didn't have with my father." He credited his son for inspiring his career and being the "motivation to go in a different direction".
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Despite this, the two have endured a fractured relationship that began when Jackson and Tompkins separated in 2008.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Their feud has been taken to social media numerous times, including in 2020 when Jackson wrote that he "used to" love his son.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson has a tattoo "Marquise" with an axe on his right biceps ("The axe is 'cause I'm a warrior.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] I don't want him to be one, though"), and has "50", "Southside" and "Cold World" on his back: "I'm a product of that environment.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] It's on my back, though, so it's all behind me".
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In 2003, Jackson dated actress Vivica A.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson dated model Daphne Joy and had his second son, Sire Jackson, with her, on September 1, 2012.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] At age two, Sire modeled for Kidz Safe, a headphone brand for kids, earning $700,000.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] I've been good to me." He also opened up about his decision to not marry, saying, "I'm safe.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] I made some mistakes, just not that one. ...
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In 2005, Jackson supported President George W.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Bush after rapper Kanye West criticized Bush for a slow response to the victims of Hurricane Katrina.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Had his felony convictions not prevented him from voting, he said, he would have voted for Bush.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson later said that Bush "has less compassion than the average human.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] By all means, I don't aspire to be like George Bush." In September 2007, he told *Time* that although he would not endorse a candidate in 2008, he "liked Hillary [Clinton]".
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Six months later, Jackson told MTV News that he had switched his support to Barack Obama after hearing him speak but had lost interest in politics.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Asked his opinion of Obama's 2012 endorsement of same-sex marriage, Jackson said, "I'm for it ...
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] I've engaged in fetish areas a couple times." He had been criticized for anti-gay comments in the past.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson endorsed Democratic nominee Hillary Clinton in the run-up to the 2016 U.S. presidential election.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] He rejected an offer of $500,000 from the Donald Trump campaign to make an appearance on Trump's behalf.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In 2020 he endorsed Trump due to his dislike of Joe Biden's tax plans.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] A week later, he retracted his endorsement, writing on Twitter, "Fuck Donald Trump, I never liked him", and endorsed Biden.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In June 2025, Jackson posted on Instagram a video of New York City mayoral candidate Zohran Mamdani explaining his tax policy, writing: "I'm not feeling this plan no.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] I will give him $258,750 and a first class one way ticket away from NY.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] He was arrested again three weeks later, when police searched his home and found heroin, ten ounces of crack cocaine and a starter's pistol.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Although Jackson was sentenced to three to nine years in prison, he served six months in a boot camp (where he earned his high-school equivalency diploma).
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] According to him, he did not use cocaine.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson and four members of his entourage were arrested shortly before 2 a.m. on December 31, 2002, when police found a .25-caliber handgun and a .45-caliber pistol in a parked car (which they searched due to its tinted windows) outside a Manhattan nightclub.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] The rapper was charged with two counts of criminal possession of a weapon.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson was sentenced to two years' probation on July 22, 2005, for a May 2004 incident, when he was charged with three counts of assault and battery after jumping into an audience when he was hit by a water bottle.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Jackson filed a lawsuit against an advertising company, Traffix of Pearl River, New York, on July 21, 2007, for using his image in a promotion he said threatened his safety.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] He was alerted by a staff member to an Internet advertisement on a Myspace page.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] According to court documents, the advertisement had a cartoon image of the rapper with "Shoot the rapper and you will win $5000 or five ring tones guaranteed".
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Although the ad did not use his name, the image allegedly resembled him and suggested that he endorsed the product.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] The lawsuit, calling the ad a "vile, tasteless and despicable" use of Jackson's image which "quite literally call[ed] for violence against him", sought unspecified punitive damages and a permanent injunction against the use of his image without permission.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In 2008, Jackson sued Taco Bell over an ad campaign that used his name without permission, in which it invited him to change his name for one day from 50 Cent to 79 Cent, 89 Cent, or 99 Cent, in line with pricing for some of its items, and they would donate $10,000 to the charity of his choice.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] The case was settled out of court in his favor in November 2009.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] While walking through Cincinnati/Northern Kentucky International Airport in May 2016, Jackson harassed and insulted a janitor at the airport, accusing him of being under the influence.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] The janitor was a hearing-impaired, autistic teenager named Andrew Farrell.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] The parents of the janitor had seen the viral video as disrespect and wanted to sue Jackson for his action against their child.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] The lawsuit was originally over one million dollars, but the parents settled for a $100,000 donation to Autism Speaks and his apology.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In 2016, a judge declared that Brandon Parrott gave Dr.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] One of his New York homes, purchased for $2.4 million in January 2007 and the center of a lawsuit between Jackson and Shaniqua Tompkins, caught fire on May 30, 2008, while he was filming in Louisiana.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] On August 5, 2013, Jackson pleaded not guilty to one count of domestic violence and four counts of vandalism in a Los Angeles County court.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] If convicted of all charges, he faced up to five years in prison and a $46,000 fine.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Model-actress Daphne Joy accused Jackson of kicking her and ransacking her bedroom during an argument at her condominium in the Toluca Lake neighborhood of Los Angeles on June 23.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] He allegedly caused $7,100 in property damage, leaving the scene before police arrived.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] Judge Ann Nevins has ordered Jackson back to court because of Instagram messages he made over several months.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] She said Jackson was not fully clear about his funds and indicated posts of the rapper showing stacks of his money.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In March 2016, Jackson claimed that he would no longer use Instagram, electing instead to have his profile page operated by someone else.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In June 2018, after former linebacker and actor Terry Crews gave a speech before the United States Senate Committee on the Judiciary in which he described being groped by a Hollywood agent in 2016, Jackson posted a photo on Instagram of a shirtless muscular Crews with the caption: "I got raped.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p01] In 2020, Jackson was a subject of controversy for his involvement in a viral video of him giving money to a Burger King restaurant in New York City on behalf of a local scammer who was later arrested and charged for Bitcoin scamming and for assaulting and kidnapping his victims on April 24, 2021.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] Before he signed with Interscope Records, Jackson engaged in a public dispute with rapper Ja Rule and his label, Murder Inc.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] Records, saying that a friend robbed jewelry from Ja Rule and the latter accused him of orchestrating the robbery.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] Ja Rule said that the conflict stemmed from a Queens video shoot, when Jackson did not like seeing him "getting so much love" from the neighborhood.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] At The Hit Factory in New York in March 2000, Jackson had an altercation with Murder Inc. associates and received three stitches for a stab wound.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] Rapper Black Child claimed responsibility for the stabbing, saying that he acted in self-defense when he thought someone reached for a gun.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] An affidavit by an Internal Revenue Service (IRS) agent suggested ties between Murder Inc. and Kenneth "Supreme" McGriff, a New York drug lord suspected of involvement in the murder of Jam Master Jay and Jackson's shooting.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] The end of the Jackson-Ja Rule feud was confirmed in May 2011.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] You don't have to be at war with somebody, but it's also kind of like U.S. and another country that they may not get along with.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] We don't gotta go to war, but we're not friends either.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] On August 7, 2015, the feud between the two rappers later reignited when Ja Rule gave a feedback to a social follower via Twitter over a similar feud between Meek Mill and Drake.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] Enraged, Jackson later responded with photos and comments via Instagram, only siding with Drake.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] The feud resurfaced three years later on January 19, 2018, when Ja Rule took to Twitter, calling out 50 Cent on social media.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] In 1999, with the release of the single "How to Rob", 50 Cent attacked his rap peers, including Jay-Z, who responded to the provocation with the single "It's Hot (Some Like It Hot)" in which he raps "Go against Jigga yo ass is dense/I'm about a dollar – what the f*ck is 50 Cents?".
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] What I did was Freeway went out and found his publishing deal, and we started the album. [...] when it came time to put the record out, he didn't want to shoot his video.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] He has a god complex." 50 Cent also accused Jay-Z of changing in attitude and image since marrying Beyoncé.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] In 2017, 50 Cent described Jay-Z's thirteenth studio album *4:44* as "golf course music" in an Instagram post, elaborating: "I listened to Jay sh*t, that *4:44*. [...] [It] was too smart.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] I felt like I was supposed to be wearing like glasses and shit and like a tie, a fucking sweater around my waist.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] They don't wanna hear that shit. [...] They just wanna have a good time.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] You can't be the best rapper at 47 because the new n****s is here.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] They coming with new [music] going on." In an interview on the *Conan Show*, 50 Cent spoke about the album, saying: "Hip-hop culture's connected to youth culture.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] The kids gonna bring new innovative stuff.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] He just had the maturity bleed off into the material. [...] But the kids, I don't see them actually listening to it".
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] In an interview in 2022, 50 Cent reported that in a meeting between him and the couple in Los Angeles, the two rappers were having a heated argument.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] Beyoncé, seeing them, jumped from a ledge to come to her husband's defense.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] 50 Cent compared the singer to her sister Solange when she hit Jay-Z in the elevator, describing them as "two gangstas".
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] In an interview for *XXL Mag* in 2023, 50 Cent claimed that Jay-Z's Grammy wins were due to his marriage to Beyoncé: "Even Jay-Z's career, you can look at that and say the association to Beyoncé is when he started to receive the 16, 17 Grammys, since he's been with Beyoncé.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] That came with the association." 50 Cent also pointed out that the couple's eldest child Blue Ivy Carter won a Grammy even though she does not sing or rap, accusing award ceremonies of giving accolades to the couple just to ensure their attendance during the show.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] The rapper also reported that his non-win at the Grammys was due to his music being "a little bit abrasive to conservatives; [...] It didn't matter to me in that time period.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] They didn't give me Best New Artist and I sold 13 million records", while the Carter-Knowles family is more politically agreeable to the music industry.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] In connection to his feud with Ja Rule, 50 Cent also took aim at fellow New York rapper Fat Joe, a high-profile collaborator of Ja Rule's.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] The feud took aim at Fat Joe following his 2002 track "What's Luv?" featuring Ja Rule and Ashanti.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] Fat Joe had also continued his collaboration with Murder Inc. on his 2004 track "New York" featuring Jadakiss, prompting a diss track aimed at Fat Joe from 50 Cent on his 2005 album *The Massacre* entitled "Piggy Bank".
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] Fat Joe later responded with the track "My Fofo" on his album *All or Nothing* released later that same year.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] Tensions boiled over during the 2005 MTV Video Music Awards when Fat Joe presented the award for best Hip Hop Video, in which he told the audience "I feel so safe tonight with all this police protection courtesy of G-Unit".
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] 50 Cent later retaliated with a profanity-laden diatribe following his performance of the song "So Seductive" with fellow G-Unit artist Tony Yayo, exclaiming "Fat Joe's a pussy man! [...] Pussy Boy, Nigga What?!".
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] The feud later affected Fat Joe financially as he sought to secure a $20 million contract endorsing Air Jordan sneakers in early 2005, Michael Jordan himself later cancelled the contract following the VMA incident as he was in fear of conflict with 50 Cent or any other affiliates.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] Following this; little action was taken on either side as the feud seemed to calm down by 2011.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] Murder Inc. executive Irv Gotti later expressed anger at Fat Joe following his proposal to quell their longstanding feud with G-Unit in 2010.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] In 2012, 50 Cent approached Fat Joe in talks of ending the feud following the two agreeing to perform at a memorial ceremony for then-recently deceased music executive Chris Lighty.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] Despite the prior history between the two, 50 Cent and Fat Joe became close friends and business associates shortly thereafter despite Fat Joe's lengthy connections with Ja Rule.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] Although Jackson was close to The Game before the latter released his debut album, *The Documentary*, they grew apart.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] After *The Documentary*'s release, Jackson felt that The Game was disloyal for saying that he did not want to participate in G-Unit's feuds with other rappers (such as Nas, Jadakiss and Fat Joe) and his desire to work with artists with which G-Unit was feuding.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] He said that he wrote six songs for the album and did not receive proper credit, which The Game denied.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] Jackson later dismissed The Game from G-Unit on Hot 97.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] After the announcement, The Game (a guest earlier in the evening) tried to enter the building with his entourage.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] After they were denied entry, one of his associates was shot in the leg in a confrontation with a group of men leaving the building.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] When the situation escalated, the rappers held a joint press conference announcing their reconciliation, and fans were uncertain if the rappers had staged a publicity stunt to boost sales of their recently released albums.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] After the situation cooled, G-Unit criticized The Game's street credibility and announced that they would not appear on his albums.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] During a Summer Jam performance The Game announced a boycott of G-Unit, which he called "G-Unot".
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] After the Summer Jam performance The Game recorded "300 Bars and Runnin'", an extended "diss" of G-Unit and Roc-A-Fella Records, for the mixtape *You Know What It Is Vol.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] Jackson responded with his "Piggy Bank" music video, with The Game as Mr.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] Potato Head and parodies of other rivals.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] They have continued attacking each other, with The Game releasing two more mixtapes: *Ghost Unit* and a mixtape-DVD, *Stop Snitchin, Stop Lyin*.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] Jackson superimposed The Game's head on the body of a male stripper for the cover of the *Hate It or Love It (G-Unit Radio Part 21)* mixtape in response to The Game's pictures of G-Unit dressed as the Village People.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] The Game, under contract to Aftermath Entertainment, signed with Geffen Records to terminate his contractual obligations with G-Unit (although it is claimed that Jackson pressured Dr.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] G-Unit member Spider Loc has insulted The Game in songs, and the latter released "240 Bars (Spider Joke)" and "100 Bars (The Funeral)" attacking G-Unit and Loc.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] Jackson's response was "Not Rich, Still Lyin'", mocking The Game.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] Lloyd Banks replied to the Game on a *Rap City* freestyle-booth segment, followed by a Game "diss" song ("SoundScan") ridiculing the 13-position drop of Banks' album *Rotten Apple* on the *Billboard* 200 chart and its disappointing second-week sales.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] Banks replied on his mixtape *Mo' Money In The Bank Pt.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] 5: Gang Green Season Continues* with "Showtime (The Game's Over)", said that Jackson wrote half of *The Documentary* and ridiculed The Game's suicidal thoughts.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] In October 2006, The Game made a peace overture (which was not immediately answered) to Jackson, but two days later he said on Power 106 that the peace offer was valid for only one day.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] In several songs on *Doctor's Advocate*, he implied that the feud was over.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] He said in July 2009 that the feud had ended with help from Michael Jackson and Sean Combs, and apologized for his actions.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] According to Tony Yayo, neither Jackson nor G-Unit accepted his apology and The Game has resumed his calls for a "G-Unot" boycott at concerts.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] Jackson released "So Disrespectful" on *Before I Self Destruct*, targeting Jay-Z, The Game and Young Buck.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] The Game responded with "Shake", poking fun at the music video for Jackson's "Candy Shop".
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] On January 2, 2015, The Game claimed that he and 50 were "sworn enemies", promising never to reconcile with him anymore, but on August 1, 2016, they ended their twelve-year feud when the two were in the Ace of Diamonds strip club and The Game said "I love 50, man.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] In January 2022, the feud reignited after 50 critiqued Game's *Drink Champs* interview with N.O.R.E., where he claimed that 50's former competitor Kanye West did "more for me in two weeks than [Dr.] Dre did for me throughout my entire career".
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] The Game responded, commenting that he enclosed the entirety of G-Unit as a group and clothing brand "in a casket", also expressing his likeliness in the *Power* television trilogy, but warning 50 to "leave [the past] alone or else...
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] Then, two months later, in March, 50 Cent published a video via Instagram of Game being shunned by former Interscope Records CEO Jimmy Iovine at a basketball game, poking fun of it while also commenting "50 wrote ya hits".
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] The Game once again flamed 50 after the claims were brought back up and also bragged to "get [50's] girlfriend out of my DM's".
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] This was believed to have been a consequential result of Game claiming on *Drink Champs* to be "the best and a better rapper" than Eminem, with whom 50 still remains close friends.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] Additionally, Game's manager, Wack 100, has subliminally called out or questioned 50 Cent's credibility, over the rapper's surprise appearance at the Super Bowl LVI halftime show and ghostwriting allegations.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] Jackson's issues with former The Diplomats member Cam'ron began in 2007, when they had a live argument on *The Angie Martinez Show* on Hot 97 radio.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] Jackson commented that he felt that the music division of Koch Entertainment (known today as MNRK Music Group) was a "graveyard", meaning major record labels would not work with their artists.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] Both rappers released diss songs with videos on YouTube.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] Jackson released "Funeral Music", and suggested in the song that Cam'ron is no longer able to lead The Diplomats and that Jim Jones should take his place.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] Cam'ron responded with "Curtis" and "Curtis Pt.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] II", in which he makes fun of not only Jackson's first name, but also his appearance, calling him "a gorilla, with rabbit teeth".
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] Jackson responded by releasing "Hold On" with Young Buck.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] Since 2009, the feud slowly died down, and they eventually reconciled in 2016.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] Although Rick Ross began a feud with Jackson over an alleged incident at the 2008 BET Hip Hop Awards, Jackson told news sources he did not remember seeing Ross there.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] Later that month Ross' "Mafia Music" was leaked on the Internet, with lyrics apparently disparaging Jackson.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] Several days later, Jackson released "Officer Ricky (Go Head, Try Me)" in response to "Mafia Music".
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] The following day, Ross appeared on Shade 45 (Eminem's Sirius channel) and told Jackson to come up with something better in 24 hours.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] Before leaving for Venezuela, Jackson uploaded a video ("Warning Shot") and the first of a series of "Officer Ricky" cartoons.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] In early February he uploaded a YouTube video in which he interviewed "Tia", the mother of one of Ross' children; according to her, Ross is in reality a correctional officer.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] On February 5, 2009, The Game phoned Seattle radio station KUBE.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] On his album *Deeper Than Rap*, Ross refers to Jackson in "In Cold Blood" and Jackson's mock funeral is part of the song's video.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] When the song was released, Ross said that he ended Jackson's career.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] He's Albert," Jackson replied in an interview.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] Gunplay's Maybach Music diamond necklace was stolen during the brawl, and several days later Jackson appeared at a Washington, D.C. bowling alley wearing Gunplay's chain.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] On January 30, 2013, Jackson tweeted that Ross' attempted drive-by shooting on his birthday three days earlier was "staged".
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] Jackson and Floyd Mayweather Jr. were close friends in the early 2000s, sharing key personal milestones including Mayweather's birthday party in Las Vegas in 2007.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] In 2012, he and Jackson co-founded the company "The Money Team" also known as “TMT”, which signs up-and-coming boxers.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] On December 21, 2011, Mayweather was sentenced to 90 days in county jail for domestic violence and battery.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] He started serving his sentence on June 1, leaving Jackson to run the promotion company.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] Mayweather was released two months later on August 3.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] Jackson then claimed Mayweather owed him $1 million for work done for TMT during Mayweather's jail sentence.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] This caused a public dispute in which the two traded insults via online videos.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] Jackson then claimed Mayweather couldn't read and challenged him to read a full Harry Potter book in exchange for a donation of $750,000 to a charity of Mayweather's choosing.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] Mayweather rejected the challenge and insulted Jackson's strained relationship with his son, offering Jackson $1 million if he could post a video of his son saying "I love you".
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] They continued to trade insults until in 2022, when Jackson & Mayweather reconciled in Las Vegas.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] Jackson's feud with Sean "Diddy" Combs began in 2006, when Jackson accused Combs of complicity in Biggie's murder in his diss track "The Bomb".
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] Over the following decades, Jackson publicly criticized Combs several times, including insulting his rival vodka brand Cîroc (Jackson endorsed Effen) and complaining that Combs made him uncomfortable when he invited him to go shopping.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] In 2023, when Combs' ex-girlfriend Cassie Ventura accused him of domestic abuse and rape, Jackson again taunted Combs, jokingly offering to take his place in endorsement deals that had abandoned Combs, and posting about the police raid on Combs' home.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] When CNN released video corroborating Cassie's allegation that Combs punched her, Jackson told the Hollywood Reporter "When someone watches that, if they have a daughter and they can imagine her being under those circumstances, that shit is crazy.
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] Jackson has also stated he never attended any of the parties Combs hosted at which the latter was accused of engaging in sex trafficking, saying the parties had an "uncomfortable energy".
[src:african-american-music/50-cent-p02] In 2024, Jackson announced he was executive producing a documentary about Combs sexual abuse and sex trafficking case, *Sean Combs: The Reckoning*, released on Netflix on December 2, 2025.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Randolph was born and raised in Florida.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] He was educated at Cookman Institute, then moved to New York City as part of the early Great Migration, leaving behind the discriminatory Jim Crow–era south.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] There he became convinced that overcoming racism required collective action and he was drawn to socialism and workers' rights.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] He unsuccessfully ran for state office on the socialist ticket in the early 1920s, but found more success in organizing for African American workers' rights.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] In 1963, Randolph was the head of the March on Washington, organized by Bayard Rustin, at which Reverend Martin Luther King Jr. delivered his "I Have a Dream" speech.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Randolph inspired the "Freedom Budget", sometimes called the "Randolph Freedom budget", which aimed to deal with the economic problems facing the Black community.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] It was published by the Randolph Institute in January 1967 as "A Freedom Budget for All Americans".
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Asa Philip Randolph was born April 15, 1889, in Crescent City, Florida, the second son of James William Randolph, a tailor and minister in an African Methodist Episcopal Church, and Elizabeth Robinson Randolph, a seamstress.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] In 1891, the family moved to Jacksonville, Florida, which had a thriving, well-established African-American community.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Randolph's father taught him that color was less important than a person's character and conduct.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] His mother taught him the importance of education and of defending oneself physically against those who tried to hurt one or one's family, if necessary.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Randolph remembered vividly the night his mother sat in the front room of their house with a loaded shotgun across her lap, while his father tucked a pistol under his coat and went off to prevent a mob from lynching a man at the local county jail.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Asa and his brother, James, were superior students.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] They attended the Cookman Institute in East Jacksonville, the only academic high school in Florida for African Americans.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Asa excelled in literature, drama, and public speaking; he also starred on the school's baseball team, sang solos with the school choir, and was valedictorian of the 1907 graduating class.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] After graduation, Randolph worked odd jobs and devoted his time to singing, acting, and reading.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Du Bois's *The Souls of Black Folk* convinced him that the fight for social equality was most important.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Barred by discrimination from all but manual jobs in the South, Randolph moved to New York City in 1911, where he worked odd jobs and took social sciences courses at City College.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] In 1913, Randolph courted and married Lucille Campbell Green, a widow, Howard University graduate, and entrepreneur who shared his socialist politics.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] She earned enough money to support them both.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Shortly after Randolph's marriage, he helped organize the Shakespearean Society in Harlem.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] With them he played the roles of Hamlet, Othello, and Romeo, among others.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Randolph aimed to become an actor but gave up after failing to win his parents' approval.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Randolph's background as a Shakespearean actor gave him a "deep, resonant voice" that he used to considerable effect in his speeches while his dignified, "courtly" bearing assisted with negotiations.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] In New York, Randolph became familiar with socialism and the ideologies espoused by the Industrial Workers of the World.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] He met Columbia University law student Chandler Owen, and the two developed a synthesis of Marxist economics and the sociological ideas of Lester Frank Ward, arguing that people could be free only if not subject to economic deprivation.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] At this point, Randolph developed what became his distinctive form of civil rights activism, which emphasized the importance of collective action as a way for Black people to gain legal and economic equality.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] To this end, he and Owen opened an employment office in Harlem to provide job training for southern migrants and encourage them to join trade unions.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Like others in the labor movement, Randolph favored immigration restriction.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] He opposed African Americans' having to compete with people willing to work for low wages.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] But unlike other immigration restrictionists, he rejected the notions of racial hierarchy that became popular in the 1920s.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] In 1917, Randolph and Owen founded *The Messenger* with the help of the Socialist Party of America.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] It was a radical monthly magazine that campaigned against lynching, opposed U.S. participation in World War I, and urged African Americans to resist being drafted, fight for an integrated society, and join radical unions.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Soon thereafter, the editorial staff of *The Messenger* became divided by three issues: the growing rift between West Indian and African Americans, support for the Bolshevik revolution, and support for Marcus Garvey's Back-to-Africa movement.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] In 1919, most West Indian radicals joined the new Communist Party, while African-American leftists—Randolph included—mostly supported the Socialist Party.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] The infighting left *The Messenger* short of financial support, and it went into decline.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Randolph unsuccessfully ran on the Socialist Party ticket for New York State Comptroller in 1920 and for Secretary of State of New York in 1922.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Randolph's first experience with labor organization came in 1917, when he organized a union of elevator operators in New York City.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] In 1919 he became president of the National Brotherhood of Workers of America, a union that organized among African-American shipyard and dock workers in the Tidewater region of Virginia.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] The union dissolved in 1921 under pressure from the American Federation of Labor.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Randolph's greatest success came with the Brotherhood of Sleeping Car Porters (BSCP), which elected him president in 1925.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] This was the first serious effort to form a labor institution for employees of the Pullman Company, a major employer of African Americans.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] The railroads had dramatically expanded in the early 20th century, and the jobs offered relatively good employment at a time of widespread racial discrimination.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] But because porters were not unionized, most had poor working conditions and were underpaid.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Under Randolph's direction, the BSCP enrolled 51 percent of porters within a year, to which Pullman responded with violence and firings.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] In 1928, after failing to win mediation under the Watson-Parker Railway Labor Act, Randolph planned a strike.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] This was postponed after rumors circulated that Pullman had 5,000 replacement workers ready to take the place of BSCP members.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] As a result of its perceived ineffectiveness, membership in the union declined; by 1933 it had only 658 members and electricity and telephone service at headquarters had been disconnected because of nonpayment of bills.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] The American historian William Harris wrote: "Randolph functioned mainly as a symbolic figure and spokesman.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] He was in the tradition of those Black leaders—they can be seen in the church and Black advancement organizations, as well as in politics—whose influence has derived largely from rhetoric and personal presence.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] But despite his superb rhetorical abilities and presence, Randolph was indecisive and prone to compromise".
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Harris described Randolph as the most charismatic Afro-American leader of his generation, writing: "Handsome, almost exquisite in bearing, and a master of the arts of oratory and rhetoric, his speech had a hypnotic effect upon his audience.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] The BSCP's fortunes changed with the 1932 election of President Franklin D.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] With amendments to the Railway Labor Act in 1934, porters were granted rights under federal law.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Membership in the Brotherhood jumped to more than 7,000.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] After years of bitter struggle, the Pullman Company began to negotiate with the Brotherhood in 1935, and agreed to a contract with it in 1937.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Employees gained $2,000,000 in pay increases, a shorter workweek, and overtime pay.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Randolph maintained the Brotherhood's affiliation with the American Federation of Labor through the 1955 AFL-CIO merger.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Through his success with the BSCP, Randolph emerged as one of the most visible spokespeople for African-American civil rights.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] He called shaping public opinion "the most powerful weapon in America" and by 1940 had become the face of the U.S. civil rights movement.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] In September 1940, at the annual BSCP convention in Harlem, Randolph urged the Roosevelt administration to have no discrimination in the Selective Training and Service Act, which was being debated in Congress at the time.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt was a speaker at the convention, and through her, Randolph obtained a meeting at the White House with President Franklin D.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] At the meeting, Roosevelt promised Randolph there would be no segregation in the military, saying he was sympathetic to the civil rights movement.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Two weeks later, the War Department issued a statement saying "the policy of the War Department is not to intermingle colored and white enlisted personnel".
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Feeling betrayed, Randolph launched nationwide protests demanding the end of segregation in not only the military but also the industries that made weapons for it.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] At the time, the Roosevelt administration was gearing up to make the U.S.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] "the arsenal of democracy" by supplying a massive number of weapons to the United Kingdom and its allies that were fighting in World War II, and banning segregation in the defense-related industry would be a huge gain for the civil rights movement.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Randolph told an aide: "I think we ought to have 10,000 Negros march down Pennsylvania Avenue...We shall not call upon our white friends to march with us.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] There are some things that Negros must do on their own".
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] In 1941, Randolph, Bayard Rustin, and A.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Muste proposed a march on Washington to protest racial discrimination in war industries, an end to segregation, access to defense employment, the proposal of an anti-lynching law, and the desegregation of the U.S. armed forces.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Randolph's belief in the power of peaceful direct action was inspired partly by Mahatma Gandhi's success using such tactics during the Indian independence movement.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Randolph threatened to have 50,000 Black people march on Washington.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] In early May 1941, Randolph made the call for a march on Washington, which generated immense enthusiasm among Afro-Americans.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] On 18 June 1941, Randolph again met with Roosevelt at the White House with the mayor of New York, Fiorello La Guardia, serving as a mediator.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Roosevelt asked Randolph to call off the march, saying "questions like this cannot be settled with a sledgehammer", and vaguely promised to have discussions if the march was canceled.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Randolph said the march would not be canceled unless Roosevelt gave way.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] La Guardia broke the impasse by saying: "Gentlemen, it is clear that Mr.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Randolph is not going to call off the march, and I suggest we all begin to seek a formula".
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] The march was canceled after Roosevelt issued Executive Order 8802, or the Fair Employment Act.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Some activists, including Rustin, felt betrayed because Roosevelt's order banned discrimination only in war industries, not the armed forces.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Nonetheless, the Fair Employment Act is generally considered an important early civil rights victory.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Executive Order 8802 read: "There shall be no discrimination in the employment of workers in defense industries or the government because of race, creed, color or national origin".
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Randolph dropped his demand for an integrated military, which he seems to have privately regarded as unrealistic and only made as a bargaining chip in his talks with Roosevelt.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] The draft involved young men from all 48 states, and the bloc of conservative Southern whites in Congress would have fiercely fought an executive order for an integrated military.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] By contrast, most of the defense-related industry was in the Northeast, the Midwest, and California, so executive Order 8802 had only limited impact in the South.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] The proposed march on Washington was a turning point in the civil rights movement.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] One Black newspaper wrote at the time, "it demonstrated to the Doubting Thomases among us that only mass action can pry open the doors that have been erected against America's Black minority".
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Before 1941, Black leaders had generally sought to lobby white politicians to change the laws.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] After 1941, there was a tendency to bypass politicians and instead engage in protests.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Executive Order 8802 led to an exodus of Black people out of the South comparable to the Great Migration of the early 20th century.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] For example, in every month of 1942, about 10,000 Afro-Americans from the South, mostly from Texas and Louisiana, settled in the Los Angeles area, to take jobs in the well-paying aviation industry.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] The movement continued to gain momentum.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Unlike World War I, Randolph supported the war effort in World War II under the slogan "Double Victory", meaning victory over fascism abroad and racism at home.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] In 1942, an estimated 18,000 Black people gathered at Madison Square Garden to hear Randolph kick off a campaign against discrimination in the military, war industries, government agencies, and labor unions.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] In 1943, Randolph visited Memphis to launch a personal campaign for free speech after E.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Crump, a Democratic ally of Roosevelt, successfully used strong-arm and political pressure tactics to drive two prominent local Black Republicans, J.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Martin and Robert Church Jr., out of the city.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] After he came to Memphis, Crump denied Randolph venues and intimidated local Black leaders into declining speaking invitations by threatening them with jail.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] When Randolph urged Eleanor Roosevelt, who had friendly political ties with Crump, to do something to counter Crump's "fascist" denial of free speech, she refused.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Her reply to Randolph on December 18 read in full: "I referred your letter to a friend of mine when I received it and I am sorry it has not been answered before.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Randolph and other activists continued to press for African Americans' rights.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] In 1947, Randolph and Grant Reynolds renewed efforts to end discrimination in the armed services, forming the Committee Against Jim Crow in Military Service, later renamed the League for Non-Violent Civil disobedience.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Truman asked Congress for a peacetime draft law, Randolph urged young Black men to refuse to register.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Truman was vulnerable to defeat in 1948 and needed the support of the growing Black population in northern states, and he capitulated.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] On July 26, 1948, Truman began ending racial segregation in the armed forces with Executive Order 9981.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] In 1950, along with NAACP Executive Secretary Roy Wilkins and National Jewish Community Relations Advisory Council leader Arnold Aronson, Randolph founded the Leadership Conference on Civil Rights (LCCR), which became a major civil rights coalition.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] It coordinated a national legislative campaign on behalf of every major civil rights law since 1957.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Randolph and Rustin also formed an important alliance with Martin Luther King Jr. in 1957, when schools in the south resisted school integration after *Brown v.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Randolph and King organized the Prayer Pilgrimage for Freedom.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] In 1958 and 1959, Randolph organized Youth Marches for Integrated Schools in Washington, D.C.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] At the same time, he arranged for Rustin to teach King to organize peaceful demonstrations in Alabama and form alliances with progressive whites.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] The protests, directed by James Bevel in cities such as Birmingham and Montgomery, provoked violent backlash by police and the local Ku Klux Klan in 1963, which was captured on television and broadcast worldwide.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Rustin later said that Birmingham "was one of television's finest hours.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Randolph finally realized his vision for a March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom on August 28, 1963.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] It attracted between 200,000 and 300,000 to the nation's capital.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] The rally is often remembered as the high point of the Civil Rights Movement, and it did help keep the issue in the public consciousness.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] But when President Kennedy was assassinated three months later, civil rights legislation stalled in the Senate.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Johnson, the Civil Rights Act finally passed.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] King and Bevel deserve great credit for these legislative victories, but the importance of Randolph's contributions to the Civil Rights Movement is large.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Randolph avoided speaking publicly about his religious beliefs to avoid alienating his diverse constituencies.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Though he is sometimes identified as an atheist, particularly by his detractors, Randolph identified with the African Methodist Episcopal Church he was raised in.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] He pioneered the use of prayer protests, which became a key tactic of the civil rights movement.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] In 1973, he signed the *Humanist Manifesto II*.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Randolph died in his Manhattan apartment on May 16, 1979.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] For several years before his death, he had a heart condition and high blood pressure.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] He had no known living relatives, as his wife Lucille had died in 1963, before the March on Washington.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Randolph had a significant impact on the Civil Rights Movement from the 1930s onward.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] The Montgomery bus boycott in Alabama was directed by E.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Nixon, who had been a member of the BSCP and was influenced by Randolph's methods of nonviolent confrontation.
[src:african-american-music/a-philip-randolph] Nationwide, the Civil Rights Movement in the 1950s and 1960s used tactics pioneered by Randolph, such as encouraging African Americans to vote as a bloc, mass voter registration, and training activists for nonviolent direct action.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Born in Brooklyn and raised in Detroit, Aaliyah first gained recognition at the age of 10, when she appeared on the television show *Star Search* and performed in concert alongside Gladys Knight.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] At the age of 12, she signed with Jive Records and her uncle Barry Hankerson's Blackground Records.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Kelly, who became her mentor, as well as lead songwriter and producer of her debut album, *Age Ain't Nothing but a Number* (1994).
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] The album sold three million copies in the US and was certified double Platinum by the Recording Industry Association of America (RIAA).
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Her first single, "Back & Forth", rose to number five on the *Billboard* Hot 100.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] After allegations of an illegal marriage with Kelly, she ended her contract with Jive and signed with Atlantic Records.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Aaliyah worked with record producers Timbaland and Missy Elliott for her second album, *One in a Million* (1996), which sold three million copies in the US and more than eight million copies worldwide.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] She made her acting debut in the action film *Romeo Must Die*.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Its soundtrack was supported by her single "Try Again", the first song to top the *Billboard* Hot 100 solely through airplay.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] She subsequently filmed her starring role in *Queen of the Damned* (2002; released posthumously) and released her third album, *Aaliyah* (2001), which topped the *Billboard* 200.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] The album spawned the singles "We Need a Resolution", "Rock the Boat", and "More Than a Woman".
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] On August 25, 2001, at the age of 22, Aaliyah was killed in a plane crash along with eight other people on board, when the overloaded aircraft she was traveling in crashed shortly after takeoff.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] The pilot was later found to have traces of cocaine and alcohol in his body and was not qualified to fly the aircraft designated for the flight.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Her family filed a wrongful death lawsuit against the aircraft's operator, which was settled out of court.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] After her death, her music has continued to achieve commercial success, aided by several posthumous releases, including the compilation albums *I Care 4 U* (2002) and *Ultimate Aaliyah* (2005).
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] She has sold 8.1 million albums in the US and an estimated 24 to 32 million albums worldwide.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Aaliyah Dana Haughton was born on January 16, 1979, in Brooklyn, New York, the younger child of Diane (née Hankerson) and Michael "Miguel" Haughton, a warehouse worker.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] She was of African-American, Jamaican, and Native American descent.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Her name is the feminine form of the Arabic "Ali", meaning "highest, most exalted one, the best." She was fond of her name, calling it "beautiful" and saying she was "very proud of it" and strove to live up to her name every day.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] When she was five years old, her family moved to Detroit, Michigan, where she was raised along with her older brother, Rashad.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] In Detroit, her father began working in the warehouse business, one of his brother-in-law Barry Hankerson's widening interests.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Her mother stayed home and raised her and her brother.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Her mother enrolled her in voice lessons at an early age.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Eventually, she started performing at weddings, church choir, and charity events.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] She attended a Catholic school, Gesu Elementary, where in first grade she was cast in the stage play *Annie,* which inspired her to become an entertainer.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Aaliyah's mother was a vocalist, and her uncle Hankerson was an entertainment lawyer who had been married to Gladys Knight.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] As a child, she traveled with Knight and worked with an agent in New York City to audition for commercials and television programs, including *Family Matters*.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] After failing to land a role on the show, she continued her acting through the Gesu Players.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] In 1989, at age ten, she appeared on *Star Search*, where she performed "My Funny Valentine".
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] She chose to begin auditioning, while her mother made the decision to drop her surname.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] She auditioned for several record labels and at age 11 appeared in concerts alongside Knight.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] After attending a Gladys Knight concert with music executive Suge Knight, and seeing Aaliyah perform on stage, rapper Tupac Shakur wanted to sign her to a record deal.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Aaliyah attended Detroit schools and believed she was well-liked, but she was teased for her short stature.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] By age 15, however, she came to love her height.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Her mother told her to be happy she was small and complimented her.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Although some children disliked her, she determined that "you always have to deal with people who are jealous, but there were so few it didn't even matter.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] The majority of kids supported me, which was wonderful." Even in her adult life, she considered herself small.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] During Aaliyah's audition for acceptance to the Detroit High School for the Fine and Performing Arts, she sang "Ave Maria" in Latin.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] She held a 4.0 grade-point average when graduating from high school, stating that "I wanted to keep that 4.0.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] After Hankerson signed a distribution deal with Jive Records, he signed Aaliyah to his Blackground Records label at the age of 12.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Hankerson later introduced her to recording artist and producer R.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Kelly, who became her mentor, as well as lead songwriter and producer of her first album, recorded when she was 14.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Her debut album, *Age Ain't Nothing but a Number*, was released under her mononym "Aaliyah", by Jive and Blackground Records on May 24, 1994; it debuted at number 24 on the *Billboard* 200 chart, selling 38,000 copies in its first week.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] It peaked at number 18 on the *Billboard* 200 and it was certified two times Platinum by the RIAA.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] To date, the album has sold over 3 million copies in the US.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] In Canada, the album was certified gold by Music Canada for 50,000 copies in shipments.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] In 2014, *Vibe* magazine estimated that the album had sold six million copies globally.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Upon its release, *Age Ain't Nothing But a Number* received generally favorable reviews from music critics.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Some writers noted that Aaliyah's "silky vocals" and "sultry voice" blended with Kelly's new jack swing helped define R&B in the 1990s.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Her sound was also compared to that of female quartet En Vogue.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Christopher John Farley of *Time* magazine called the album a "beautifully restrained work", noting that her "girlish, breathy vocals rode calmly on R.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Kelly's rough beats." Stephen Thomas Erlewine of AllMusic felt that the album had its "share of filler", but described the singles as "slyly seductive." He also wrote that the songs on the album were "frequently better" than that of Kelly's second studio album, *12 Play*.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] *Billboard* criticized the single "At Your Best (You Are Love)" for being out of place on the album and for its length.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Aaliyah's debut single, "Back & Forth", peaked at number 5 on the Hot 100 and topped the Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs chart for three weeks.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Two more singles charted: a cover of the Isley Brothers' "At Your Best (You Are Love)" peaked at number 6 on the *Billboard* Hot 100, and the album's title track, "Age Ain't Nothing but a Number", peaked at number 75.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Additionally, she released "The Thing I Like" as part of the soundtrack to the 1994 film *A Low Down Dirty Shame*.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] In February 1996, Aaliyah was featured on the Kris Kross single "Live and Die for Hip Hop", which also featured Jermaine Dupri (the song's producer) and rapper Da Brat.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] That year, she left Jive Records and signed with Atlantic Records.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] She worked with record producers Timbaland and Missy Elliott, who contributed to her second studio album, *One in a Million*.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Elliott recalled Timbaland and herself being nervous to work with Aaliyah, since the latter had already released her successful debut album while Elliott and Timbaland were just starting out.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] It also generated the singles "Hot Like Fire" and "4 Page Letter".
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] *One in a Million* peaked at number 18 on the *Billboard* 200, and was certified double platinum by the RIAA on June 16, 1997, denoting shipments of two million copies.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] The album went on to sell 3 million copies in the US and over eight million copies worldwide.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] The year after her album was released, she was featured on Timbaland & Magoo's debut single, "Up Jumps da Boogie".
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] In 1997, Aaliyah graduated with a 4.0 GPA from the Detroit High School for the Fine and Performing Arts, where she majored in drama.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] The same year, she began her acting career, playing herself in the police drama television series *New York Undercover*.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] During this time, she participated in the Children's Benefit Concert, a charity concert at the Beacon Theatre in New York.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] She also became the spokesperson for the Tommy Hilfiger Corporation.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] During her campaign with Tommy Hilfiger, the company sold over 2,400 pairs of the red, white and blue baggy jeans she wore in their advertisements.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] In December 1997, she performed the Christmas carol "What Child Is This?" at the annual Christmas in Washington television special.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] She also contributed to the soundtrack album for the animated film *Anastasia*, performing a cover version of "Journey to the Past" that earned songwriters Lynn Ahrens and Stephen Flaherty a nomination for the Academy Award for Best Original Song.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] She performed the song at the 70th Academy Awards, becoming the youngest singer to perform at the event.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Also in 1998, she released the song "Are You That Somebody?", which was featured on the *Dr.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] The song peaked at number 21 on the *Billboard* Hot 100 and earned her her first Grammy Award nomination.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] In 1999, Aaliyah landed her first big-screen acting role in *Romeo Must Die*.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] She starred opposite martial artist Jet Li, playing a couple who fall in love amid their warring families.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Released on March 24, 2000, the movie grossed US$18.6 million in its first weekend, ranking number two at the box office.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] She purposely stayed away from reviews of the film to "make it easier on" herself, but heard "that people were able to get into me, which is what I wanted." In contrast, some critics felt there was no chemistry between her and Li, as well as viewing the film as too simplistic.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] This was echoed by Elvis Mitchell of *The New York Times*, who wrote that while she was "a natural" and the film was conceived as a spotlight for both her and Li, "they have so little chemistry together you'd think they're putting out a fire instead of shooting off sparks.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] In addition to acting, she served as an executive producer of the film's soundtrack, for which she contributed four songs.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] "Try Again" was released as a single from the soundtrack; the song topped the *Billboard* Hot 100, making her the first artist to top the chart based solely on airplay; this led the song to be released in a 12-inch vinyl and 7-inch single.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] The music video won the Best Female Video and Best Video from a Film awards at the 2000 MTV Video Music Awards.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] It also earned her a Grammy Award nomination for Best Female R&B Vocalist.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] The soundtrack went on to sell 1.5 million copies in the United States.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] After completing *Romeo Must Die*, Aaliyah began to work on her second film, *Queen of the Damned*.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] She played the role of an ancient vampire, Queen Akasha, which she described as a "manipulative, crazy, sexual being".
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Filming both *Romeo Must Die* and *Queen of the Damned* delayed the release of her next album.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] She had not intended for her albums to have such a gap between them: "I wanted to take a break after *One in a Million* to just relax, think about how I wanted to approach the next album.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Then, when I was ready to start back up, *Romeo* happened, and so I had to take another break and do that film and then do the soundtrack, then promote it.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] The break turned into a longer break than I anticipated." Ultimately, she filmed *Queen of the Damned* and recorded her third album at the same time, so that the album could be released in 2001.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] She enjoyed balancing her singing and acting careers.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Though she called music a "first" for her, she also had been acting since she was young and had wanted to begin acting "at some point in my career", but "wanted it to be the right time and the right vehicle" and felt *Romeo Must Die* "was it".
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] During the recording stages for the album, Aaliyah's publicist disclosed that the album's release date would most likely be October 2000.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Aaliyah finished recording the album in March 2001 after a year of recording tracks that began in March 2000.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] *Aaliyah* was released five years after *One in a Million* on July 17, 2001, and debuted at number two on the *Billboard* 200, selling 187,000 copies in its first week.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] The first single from the album, "We Need a Resolution", peaked at number 59 on the *Billboard* Hot 100.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] The week after her death, the album rose from number 19 to number 1 on the *Billboard* 200.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] "Rock the Boat" was released as a posthumous single.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] The music video premiered on BET's *Access Granted*, and it became the most viewed and highest rated episode in the history of the show.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] The song peaked at number 14 on the *Billboard* Hot 100.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Promotional posters for *Aaliyah* that had been put up in major cities such as New York and Los Angeles became makeshift memorials for grieving fans.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] In February 2002, the album was certified double Platinum by the RIAA.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Aaliyah's songs "More than a Woman" and "I Care 4 U" were released as posthumous singles and peaked within the top 25 of the *Billboard* Hot 100.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] "More than a Woman" reached number one on the UK singles chart, making her the first female deceased artist to reach number one on the UK singles chart.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] "More than a Woman" was replaced by George Harrison's "My Sweet Lord", which is the only time in the UK singles chart's history that a dead artist has replaced another dead artist at number one.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Aaliyah was signed to appear in several future films, including a romantic film titled *Some Kind of Blue* and a Whitney Houston-produced remake of the 1976 film *Sparkle*.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Houston recalled Aaliyah being "so enthusiastic" about the film; the project was shelved after she died.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Before her death, Aaliyah filmed some scenes for the sequels of *The Matrix* as the character Zee.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] A portion of her role in *The Matrix Reloaded* was filmed; these unused scenes were included in the tribute section of the *Matrix Ultimate Collection* series.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] With the release of her debut album *Age Ain't Nothing but a Number*, writer Dimitri Ehrlich of *Entertainment Weekly* compared her style and sound to R&B group En Vogue.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Ehrlich also stated that her "silky vocals are more agile than those of self-proclaimed queen of hip-hop soul Mary J.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Blige." In her review for her second studio album *One in a Million* in *Vibe* magazine, music critic Dream Hampton said that her "deliciously feline" voice had the same "pop appeal" as Janet Jackson's.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] According to *Rolling Stone,* "the most remarkable thing about Aaliyah's voice, besides its flexibility and crisp range, was its almost preternatural poise — she always seemed to be holding her power in reserve, to know every side of the scenarios she described".
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Siân Pattenden from *Mixmag* stated that "she doesn't try to toss the caber with vocal athleticism.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] There's no shouting, screeching, wailing or jazz-style noodling.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Everything is underplayed: Ms Haughton's range is displayed by the slightest high-octave backing and tiniest harmonies".
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Aaliyah said that her vocal styling consisted of singing softly while utilizing her falsetto.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] She further explained that "my signature style is breathy, tone-y, airy.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] It's simple but I can ride a crazy track." Although she frequently sang in a softer tone, there were moments when she utilized other facets of her voice.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Daryl Simmons, the producer of her song "The One I Gave My Heart To", recalled her doing opera vocal warm-up exercises in preparation for recording, stating that "it was the furthest thing I would have ever thought that she could do.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] It just blew my mind." The song's writer, Diane Warren, praised Aaliyah's vocals on the song, saying that "it showed her vocal range, and I know a couple of people thought she wouldn't be able to do that song.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] From the very beginning, Aaliyah opted "for an edgier, more mature sound", and her songs were often both uptempo and dark, revolving around "matters of the heart".
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] She "easily straddled the hip-hop and pop worlds, never projecting the frilliness of her ingénue peers".
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Kelly-produced debut album, she worked with Timbaland and Missy Elliott, whose productions were more electronic.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] The duo "mixed choppy, nervous rhythms over loops of computer-generated backing tracks, and incorporating harmonies which – within the genre's limited horizons – seemed daring".
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] They also created the "freeze-and-stop style of singing on top of bass-heavy instrumentals" that became Aaliyah's signature style.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] In 2001, she called her sound "street but sweet", pairing feminine vocals with a gritty urban rhythm track.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] In another interview, she further spoke about her artistry, saying, "I love to fuse other types of music with my own".
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] She explored a wide range of genres such as R&B, pop, hip hop, funk, soul, and dance-pop.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] *Time* music critic Christopher John Farley described her music as alternative R&B, progressive soul, and neo soul.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Aaliyah released "musically risky singles into a notoriously fickle pop market", without being "concerned about conforming to the stereotypes of the marketplace".
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Her songs "gracefully walk a line between commerciality and experimentation".
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Her records tended to have a "crisp production" and "staccato arrangements" that "extend genre boundaries" while containing "old-school" soul music.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] The only time she had a hand in writing was on the song "Death of a Playa" from the 1997 single "Hot Like Fire".
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] She co-wrote that song, which "reflects Aaliyah's dark perspective on romance", with her brother Rashad Haughton.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] She said of her role in crafting her music that "I like to have the final say but I was trained as a singer, actress and dancer, the interpreter, bringing other people's words to life.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] I need the songs to reflect me in one way or another".
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] As Aaliyah's albums progressed, writers felt that she matured, calling her progress a "near-flawless declaration of strength and independence".
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] ABC News noted that her music was "evolving from the punchy pop-influenced hip hop and R&B to a more mature, introspective sound" on her third album.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] *NME* called her third album "radical" and said that it was "intended to consolidate her position as [US] R&B's most experimental artist".
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Stephen Thomas Erlewine of AllMusic described her album *Aaliyah* as "a statement of maturity and a stunning artistic leap forward", and called it one of the strongest urban soul records of its time.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] It was described as portraying "unfamiliar sounds, styles and emotions", but managed to please critics with the contemporary sound it contained.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Ernest Hardy of *Rolling Stone* felt that she was displaying stronger technique and giving her best vocal performances on the album.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] (right) all influenced Aaliyah and her music.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] As an artist, Aaliyah said that she was inspired by a number of performers.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] These included Michael Jackson, Stevie Wonder, Sade, Trent Reznor of Nine Inch Nails, Korn, Donnie Hathaway, Johnny Mathis, Janet Jackson, Whitney Houston, and Barbra Streisand.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] She said that Michael Jackson's *Thriller* was her "favorite album" and that "nothing will ever top *Thriller*." She said that she had always wanted to work with Janet Jackson, to whom she had often been compared, saying, "I admire her a great deal.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] I'd love to do a duet with Janet Jackson." Jackson reciprocated Aaliyah's affection, saying that "I've loved her from the beginning because she always comes out and does something different, musically." Jackson said that she would have enjoyed collaborating with Aaliyah.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] That's what she was about." Christopher John Farley from *Time* magazine stated that her "videos, for the most part, are about mood, not about storylines...
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Her videos are usually lushly shot and infused with sexual tension, though not in overt and obvious ways".
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Alisha Acquaye from *Teen Vogue* wrote that "there's much to gather while watching an Aaliyah music video", and that terming it "watching" them was "actually an understatement".
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] She explained that "there's a state of hypnosis you submit to as she envelops you through sight and sound, tugging at your heartstrings.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Between a sequence of sensual, strong movements, infectious instrumentals, and intuitive lyrics that spark emotions of desire, sex, and empowerment, you are enraptured in Aaliyah's physical presence".
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Most of Aaliyah's videos included dance routines.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] While discussing her video choreography, *Billboard* mentioned that she "coined the smooth choreography and tomboyish style that would inspire [R&B]'s future generations for years to come".
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] *Vibe* praised several videos, saying that "looking back on her videos like "Try Again" and "Are You That Somebody", Aaliyah's talent in all of those techniques of dancing are apparent, as she's able to hit every syncopated word and beat with ease as if she's moving on air".
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Kyann-Sian Williams from *NME* named "Are You That Somebody?" as a video that "pushed the boundaries when it came to dance breaks in music videos".
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Williams stated that "until that time, dance breaks were usually reserved for boybands like *NSync and the Backstreet Boys, but Aaliyah claimed it for R&B stars too".
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Aaliyah focused on her public image while protecting her private life.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] She felt that it was "important ... to differentiate yourself from the rest of the pack".
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] *USA Today* said that "her slinky vocal style and eye-popping videos made her a crossover star, while her persistent protection of her privacy added an air of intrigue about her".
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] She said that "I put a lot of pressure on myself to be true to myself and not let anything else influence me to do what someone else is doing.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] I'm happy to put over that dark edge in my videos, because it's always been there.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Aaliyah often wore baggy clothes and sunglasses, stating that she wanted to be herself.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] She also wore black clothing, starting a trend for similar fashion among women in United States and Japan.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] In 1998, she hired a personal trainer to keep in shape, exercised five days a week, and ate diet foods.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] As her career progressed, she went through "many fashion revamps".
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] For example, when she changed her hairstyle, she took her mother's advice and covered her left eye, much like Veronica Lake.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] The look has become known as her signature and been referred to as a fusion of "unnerving emotional honesty" and "a sense of mystique".
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] In regards to her fashion choices, writer Jeff Lorez described her as a "model of understatement".
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] According to Lorez, "she's beautiful, but hardly in a high-gloss, supermodel way—more like a really good-looking girl next door.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] And rather than bling-blinging her ice in a ghetto-fabulous manner befitting her Trumped-up surroundings, she blings on the down-low: A subtle bracelet here, a winking pendant there, offset by her simple black jeans and matching sweater.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Former Total Request Live host Carson Daly said that she was "cutting edge, always one step ahead of the curve and that the TRL audience looks to her to figure out what's hot and what's new".
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Aaliyah was often praised for her "clean-cut image" and "moral values".
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] And then her second album, *One in a Million* went double platinum.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] She had the leading role in *Romeo Must Die*, which was a box office success.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] She's won numerous awards, several MTV music video awards, and aside from her professional successes, many of her lyrics are very inspirational and uplifting.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] She also carried herself in a very professional manner.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] She was beautiful, but she didn't use her beauty to sell her music.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] Aaliyah was also seen as a sex symbol and did not have a problem with being considered one.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] "I know that people think I'm sexy and I am looked at as that, and it is cool with me", she stated.
[src:african-american-music/aaliyah-p01] If you embrace it, it can be a very beautiful thing.
